[SPEAKER_16]: That's been my honest view over my entire adult life.

547
00:36:18,538 --> 00:36:25,989
[SPEAKER_16]: But I'm a Democrat, so I accept that we can't be an independent country until the people of Scotland vote for us to be an independent country.

548
00:36:26,589 --> 00:36:30,575
[SPEAKER_16]: And I do believe in the right of the people of Scotland to decide their own future.

549
00:36:30,615 --> 00:36:39,808
[SPEAKER_16]: I think, generally, there's an accepted view that self-determination of the right of people to decide how they should be governed is an important political principle.

550
00:36:39,788 --> 00:36:49,096
[SPEAKER_16]: And I think what politics today needs is politicians who will set out what they actually believe in, set it out openly to the public, and ask the public to judge.

551
00:36:49,116 --> 00:37:07,753
[SPEAKER_16]: And one of the frustrations I've got is that today, in the Scottish Parliament, there is a majority in favour of there being a referendum on independence, and that Scotland should be an independent country, but we're not being permitted by the United Kingdom government to put that idea and that concept to the public.

552
00:37:08,093 --> 00:37:09,795
[SPEAKER_16]: And I think we should have the right to do so.

553
00:37:09,775 --> 00:37:15,267
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, obviously there was a referendum in 2014, which you lost.

554
00:37:15,908 --> 00:37:27,413
[SPEAKER_33]: You're now saying in your manifesto, I mean, independence is front and centre, that if you win the majority of Scottish seats at Westminster, 29 I think it is, that you will consider a mandate to ask the UK government for

555
00:37:27,393 --> 00:37:30,117
[SPEAKER_33]: another way to negotiate independence.

556
00:37:30,398 --> 00:37:38,911
[SPEAKER_33]: I assume that the opposite also applies, that if you do not get that majority of 29 seats, you will also take that as a democratic decision, that you shouldn't be pursuing independence.

557
00:37:38,931 --> 00:37:45,942
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, what I want to make sure, and it's really related to the point that I answered Sam about a moment ago,

558
00:37:45,922 --> 00:37:58,723
[SPEAKER_16]: is that the legitimate decisions of the people of Scotland in the election in 2021, when a Scottish Parliament was elected with a majority of members favouring independence and a referendum, that that can actually be respected by the United Kingdom government.

559
00:37:58,743 --> 00:38:00,787
[SPEAKER_33]: But in your manifesto, you're talking about this election.

560
00:38:00,847 --> 00:38:09,962
[SPEAKER_33]: So surely you can't say, on the one hand, if we win the majority of seats, the Scottish seats at Westminster, that is giving us the green light to see if we can get another referendum.

561
00:38:10,503 --> 00:38:12,486
[SPEAKER_33]: But if you don't win them,

562
00:38:12,466 --> 00:38:14,970
[SPEAKER_33]: that is giving you the red light.

563
00:38:15,451 --> 00:38:16,632
[SPEAKER_16]: But I don't hear you saying that.

564
00:38:16,713 --> 00:38:23,884
[SPEAKER_16]: What I want is people in Scotland to confidently vote for the SNP to make sure we can turn that manifesto into a reality.

565
00:38:24,144 --> 00:38:25,666
[SPEAKER_16]: Just answer that question, John.

566
00:38:25,847 --> 00:38:32,016
[SPEAKER_16]: And we can actually deliver on what people asked the Parliament to deliver on in 2021.

567
00:38:32,156 --> 00:38:38,406
[SPEAKER_33]: If you do not get the majority of Scottish seats at Westminster, what does that tell you about your

568
00:38:38,386 --> 00:38:40,289
[SPEAKER_33]: mandate to ask for another referendum?

569
00:38:40,769 --> 00:38:44,715
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, what I want to do during the election campaign is to encourage people to vote for the SNP.

570
00:38:44,735 --> 00:38:46,096
[SPEAKER_16]: OK, so you're not answering that question.

571
00:38:46,116 --> 00:38:50,322
[SPEAKER_16]: To enable us to deliver on that policy commitment, which is right at the heart of our manifesto.

572
00:38:50,382 --> 00:38:51,544
[SPEAKER_16]: Are you going to answer that question or not?

573
00:38:51,564 --> 00:38:54,127
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, what I'm saying is that I want people to vote for the SNP to make this happen.

574
00:38:54,147 --> 00:38:54,848
[SPEAKER_33]: OK, I think that's a no.

575
00:38:55,349 --> 00:38:56,330
[SPEAKER_33]: All right, you've got a question here.

576
00:38:56,550 --> 00:38:57,271
[SPEAKER_32]: Yeah.

577
00:38:57,291 --> 00:38:58,453
[SPEAKER_33]: Hang on, let's get a microphone to you.

578
00:39:02,180 --> 00:39:03,443
[SPEAKER_32]: in England.

579
00:39:04,325 --> 00:39:10,118
[SPEAKER_32]: I work for the manufacturing centre, which you know at the moment is struggling for growth all the way through the UK.

580
00:39:10,920 --> 00:39:17,274
[SPEAKER_32]: With the SNP, it seems to me that every problem, as you guys keep saying, the road leads to Westminster.

581
00:39:17,495 --> 00:39:18,838
[SPEAKER_32]: I don't believe that that's the case.

582
00:39:19,291 --> 00:39:26,346
[SPEAKER_32]: So can you tell me specifically what the SNP would do to support the growth in the manufacturing sector?

583
00:39:26,767 --> 00:39:28,210
[SPEAKER_32]: Specifically, please.

584
00:39:28,230 --> 00:39:39,173
[SPEAKER_16]: The first thing I would do is I would argue, as we argue in our manifesto, for us to rejoin the European Union, because that, I think, is the source of the problems in the manufacturing sector.

585
00:39:41,836 --> 00:39:52,712
[SPEAKER_33]: But given that you have to go through a lot of hoops to get there, first of all, you have to secure independence, then you have to get the EU to agree for you to become part of the EU, I think you want something slightly shorter term.

586
00:39:52,732 --> 00:39:55,035
[SPEAKER_16]: I mean, that could be 10 years or something.

587
00:39:55,055 --> 00:40:01,584
[SPEAKER_16]: But my point is that there's a couple of big issues in this election campaign that really aren't seeing the light of day.

588
00:40:01,965 --> 00:40:06,932
[SPEAKER_16]: And one of them is the disastrous impact of Brexit on the United Kingdom economy.

589
00:40:06,912 --> 00:40:10,457
[SPEAKER_33]: And you are, of course, free to offer that opinion, but that is not actually the question you're being asked.

590
00:40:10,477 --> 00:40:15,043
[SPEAKER_33]: So could you answer that question, which is specifically, what will the SNP do to boost growth in manufacturing?

591
00:40:15,083 --> 00:40:15,884
[SPEAKER_33]: That's your question, isn't it?

592
00:40:16,465 --> 00:40:28,802
[SPEAKER_16]: If I look at one of the things that we're taking forward in Scotland today, we've got what's called a tech scaler programme, which is designed to take new emerging companies that have emerged from our universities and partnerships with business,

593
00:40:28,782 --> 00:40:33,007
[SPEAKER_16]: to essentially support them and to fuel the growth of those individual companies.

594
00:40:33,448 --> 00:40:38,173
[SPEAKER_16]: And what that's about doing is taking new, fresh, dynamic ideas, the ideas of the future.

595
00:40:38,474 --> 00:40:40,256
[SPEAKER_16]: There are things that are happening today in Scotland.

596
00:40:40,717 --> 00:40:46,844
[SPEAKER_16]: We've got a facility up in Shetland which is now going to start launching satellites by rocket into space.

597
00:40:47,144 --> 00:40:56,035
[SPEAKER_16]: Now, if you'd said to me a few years ago, Scotland will be a satellite-launching country, I would have said, OK, that's quite a big ask, but, you know, it'll be interesting if it happens.

598
00:40:56,436 --> 00:40:57,557
[SPEAKER_16]: It's now happening.

599
00:40:57,537 --> 00:41:11,809
[SPEAKER_16]: So innovation that comes from our universities can be fuelled with public investment and that's what the Scottish Government is doing to support that activity, to strengthen the manufacturing base of Scotland and to strengthen the economic opportunities that we face.

600
00:41:12,189 --> 00:41:13,352
[SPEAKER_16]: Does that answer your question?

601
00:41:13,838 --> 00:41:18,628
[SPEAKER_32]: time scales to me, it is a bit like the rockets going up to space.

602
00:41:18,668 --> 00:41:21,072
[SPEAKER_16]: That is happening now.

603
00:41:21,092 --> 00:41:32,455
[SPEAKER_32]: You can take one example in one situation, but at the end of the day, we all know how much we are all paid in time and money from a Brexit perspective.

604
00:41:32,958 --> 00:41:37,606
[SPEAKER_32]: talking about going back into that situation for the manufacturing sector is just not helpful.

605
00:41:38,988 --> 00:41:41,953
[SPEAKER_33]: Shall I take another question?

606
00:41:42,053 --> 00:41:43,215
[SPEAKER_33]: Thank you for your point.

607
00:41:43,235 --> 00:41:44,036
[SPEAKER_33]: There are lots of hands up.

608
00:41:44,056 --> 00:41:45,839
[SPEAKER_33]: The man in the green shirt.

609
00:41:47,923 --> 00:41:48,604
[SPEAKER_02]: Good evening, John.

610
00:41:50,087 --> 00:41:55,776
[SPEAKER_02]: As a long-term supporter of both your party and independence,

611
00:41:56,279 --> 00:42:00,989
[SPEAKER_02]: You've just said two minutes ago you want to give us the confidence to vote for you.

612
00:42:01,009 --> 00:42:16,600
[SPEAKER_02]: How can you convince me that you can lead a successful independent nation after it appears the party has destroyed itself from the top down, not from the bottom up?

613
00:42:16,985 --> 00:42:20,148
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, let me perhaps set out some of the things that we've done.

614
00:42:20,268 --> 00:42:29,676
[SPEAKER_16]: So since we came to office, for example, GDP per capita in Scotland, the growth of the economy, has been faster in Scotland than in the rest of the United Kingdom.

615
00:42:30,156 --> 00:42:36,441
[SPEAKER_16]: Productivity in the Scottish economy has grown faster under the SNP government than it has in the rest of the United Kingdom.

616
00:42:37,002 --> 00:42:46,570
[SPEAKER_16]: I said a moment ago the measures were taken to tackle child poverty, which is keeping 100,000 children out of poverty in Scotland today.

617
00:42:46,550 --> 00:42:55,523
[SPEAKER_16]: We've seen also the significant expansion of early learning and childcare, which is delivering the best start for children and young people in our society.

618
00:42:56,184 --> 00:43:12,928
[SPEAKER_16]: So what I would say is that there's a whole range of decisions that have been made in Scotland that are good for Scotland, and that's an illustration of what an independent country could do if we had the powers, the broader range of powers, because I accept we need to improve economic performance in Scotland,

619
00:43:12,908 --> 00:43:24,510
[SPEAKER_16]: we need to eradicate poverty, child poverty within our society and we can only do that if we have the broader range of powers and we've demonstrated with the limited powers that we've got how we can make a difference.

620
00:43:24,590 --> 00:43:27,315
[SPEAKER_33]: Well on that point let's hear a question from Tina Greenwood.

621
00:43:27,515 --> 00:43:30,661
[SPEAKER_33]: Keep your hands up if you want to ask because I will come to you later but Tina whereabouts are you?

622
00:43:31,142 --> 00:43:31,643
[SPEAKER_33]: Ah there you go.

623
00:43:32,230 --> 00:43:38,116
[SPEAKER_01]: If no more funding comes through from Westminster, how will you fix the NHS in Scotland?

624
00:43:38,536 --> 00:43:55,012
[SPEAKER_33]: So the NHS, just for those, forgive me, John, just for those who are south of the border who may not be aware, the NHS is a devolved department in Scotland, which means that you control, you get a block grant from the UK government overall, but you decide how much you want to spend on the NHS.

625
00:43:55,392 --> 00:43:58,255
[SPEAKER_33]: And just to put that into context,

626
00:43:58,808 --> 00:44:02,132
[SPEAKER_33]: In Scotland, just over 7,000 people are waiting over two years for treatment.

627
00:44:02,192 --> 00:44:03,594
[SPEAKER_33]: In England, it's just under 300.

628
00:44:04,736 --> 00:44:15,209
[SPEAKER_16]: So the first point I'd like to say in response to your question is that I accept there are some very significant challenges in the National Health Service in Scotland today.

629
00:44:15,790 --> 00:44:23,179
[SPEAKER_16]: And some of that's a product of the impact of COVID and the necessity of trying to catch up on cases that were delayed.

630
00:44:23,159 --> 00:44:29,687
[SPEAKER_16]: and we're making headway on the long waits that Fiona just put to me in the additional part of the question.

631
00:44:30,007 --> 00:44:36,876
[SPEAKER_16]: So I accept, first of all, that there's a real challenge in the National Health Service, and we need to put more funding in to do something about that.

632
00:44:37,416 --> 00:44:40,099
[SPEAKER_16]: There's two elements to the funding we have available to us.

633
00:44:40,119 --> 00:44:48,930
[SPEAKER_16]: There's the block grant that comes from Westminster, which is affected by the same austerity and spending constraints that affect budgets in England and Wales.

634
00:44:48,910 --> 00:44:51,014
[SPEAKER_16]: but there's also the money we can raise in Scotland.

635
00:44:51,535 --> 00:45:00,471
[SPEAKER_16]: So we've taken decisions over the last three or four years to increase tax on higher earners so we could raise more money to invest in public services.

636
00:45:00,952 --> 00:45:09,568
[SPEAKER_16]: And we now have one and a half billion pounds available to us that we invest in public services that wouldn't be there if we hadn't taken those decisions.

637
00:45:09,548 --> 00:45:19,790
[SPEAKER_16]: That's an example of how we're using the powers that we have today to try to address the very issue that you fairly put to me about the challenges in the National Health Service.

638
00:45:20,552 --> 00:45:29,110
[SPEAKER_16]: But the deeper problem we have, and this is a problem I think that we share with the rest of the United Kingdom, is a long-term effect of 14 years of austerity.

639
00:45:29,090 --> 00:45:49,094
[SPEAKER_16]: and I'm not hearing coming out of the UK election debate between the Labour Party and the Conservative Party the type of financial solution to the challenges in the National Health Service that we need to hear because there's just not enough money proposed to be invested in improving the public services of the United Kingdom and that would have an effect on Scotland as well.

640
00:45:49,114 --> 00:45:54,861
[SPEAKER_33]: Tina's question is, in a sense Tina, you're asking John Swinney to kind of live in the real world, that if there isn't

641
00:45:54,841 --> 00:45:55,762
[SPEAKER_33]: you're nodding your head.

642
00:45:55,983 --> 00:46:02,311
[SPEAKER_33]: If no more funding does come from Westminster, how are you going to fix the NHS in Scotland, which is something that you are responsible for?

643
00:46:02,371 --> 00:46:03,453
[SPEAKER_33]: That is Tina's question.

644
00:46:03,493 --> 00:46:11,564
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, my answer to that is that we'll put in the resources to try to address the most immediate issues about long waits, for example.

645
00:46:11,584 --> 00:46:16,350
[SPEAKER_16]: So we've put in £30 million to address some of the long waits issues, and that's currently being deployed.

646
00:46:16,370 --> 00:46:18,233
[SPEAKER_33]: So how do you explain that discrepancy?

647
00:46:18,213 --> 00:46:20,796
[SPEAKER_33]: Thousands of people waiting over tears for treatment in Scotland.

648
00:46:21,137 --> 00:46:25,463
[SPEAKER_33]: In England, I mean waiting is bad in England as well, but when it comes to waiting over tears, it's just 300.

649
00:46:25,523 --> 00:46:27,606
[SPEAKER_33]: How is that happening?

650
00:46:27,706 --> 00:46:37,819
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, I suspect what it probably has to do with is just about the nature of some of the complex health conditions that people are experiencing and how they are addressed.

651
00:46:37,839 --> 00:46:39,822
[SPEAKER_16]: But there will be other indicators of performance.

652
00:46:39,842 --> 00:46:47,292
[SPEAKER_16]: For example, Scotland has the best performing accident and emergency system in the United Kingdom and has had for the last 10 years.

653
00:46:47,272 --> 00:46:55,041
[SPEAKER_16]: So there will be other aspects of looking at the health service to see how we're doing things differently that are performing better than other parts of the UK.

654
00:46:55,201 --> 00:46:58,005
[SPEAKER_33]: And I can give examples where you're also doing worse.

655
00:46:58,025 --> 00:47:01,829
[SPEAKER_16]: And there will be lessons that we've got to learn from other parts of the United Kingdom.

656
00:47:01,849 --> 00:47:12,942
[SPEAKER_16]: But my core point is that I just don't think the election debate in the UK is a realistic debate about the investment that is required in our public services.

657
00:47:12,922 --> 00:47:19,173
[SPEAKER_16]: We all, I think, there is a crisis created by 14 years of austerity and we have to address that.

658
00:47:19,514 --> 00:47:22,920
[SPEAKER_33]: There's a woman there with glasses, yeah.

659
00:47:22,940 --> 00:47:32,297
[SPEAKER_39]: You said earlier that you want to try and bring people in Scotland together, but how do you think you can actually go about bringing people in Scotland together when you're campaigning for a second divisive independence referendum?

660
00:47:32,446 --> 00:47:36,575
[SPEAKER_16]: I think it's about having a democratic debate and coming to those conclusions.

661
00:47:37,117 --> 00:47:39,221
[SPEAKER_16]: And having that debate in a respectful fashion.

662
00:47:39,462 --> 00:47:43,892
[SPEAKER_16]: I bring to my politics a respectful contribution about other parties.

663
00:47:44,112 --> 00:47:48,362
[SPEAKER_16]: I think, I look at politics just now, I've been involved in politics a long time.

664
00:47:48,342 --> 00:47:51,666
[SPEAKER_16]: I've never seen politics in as bad condition as it is today.

665
00:47:51,926 --> 00:47:58,113
[SPEAKER_16]: It is very fractured, not just in Scotland or the United Kingdom, in a much wider sense.

666
00:47:58,654 --> 00:48:08,185
[SPEAKER_16]: So I think it's incumbent on political leaders, and particularly on me as the First Minister of Scotland, to do all that I can to try to bring people together by respectful, courteous debate.

667
00:48:08,545 --> 00:48:09,947
[SPEAKER_16]: And that's how I go about my business.

668
00:48:10,487 --> 00:48:11,228
[SPEAKER_33]: And in the blue shirt.

669
00:48:11,832 --> 00:48:12,793
[SPEAKER_04]: Hi there.

670
00:48:13,474 --> 00:48:19,362
[SPEAKER_04]: So in 2016, Scotland voted as a majority to remain in the EU.

671
00:48:19,923 --> 00:48:37,688
[SPEAKER_04]: Surely that means that if it's the Scottish people's will to remain in the EU, that we should be allowed another referendum on, say, freedom of movement, the customs union, or even if it is the road to rejoining the EU, independence, because that's what Scotland wants to remain part of the EU.

672
00:48:37,668 --> 00:48:43,981
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, I think it's a very good point, because in 2016, Scotland voted emphatically to stay in the European Union.

673
00:48:44,522 --> 00:48:54,963
[SPEAKER_16]: And one of the things we were told in the 2014 independence referendum in Scotland was that our European Union membership was guaranteed by voting no to independence.

674
00:48:55,424 --> 00:48:59,372
[SPEAKER_16]: And two years later, the absolute opposite of what was promised

675
00:48:59,555 --> 00:49:00,879
[SPEAKER_16]: actually came to pass.

676
00:49:01,440 --> 00:49:14,897
[SPEAKER_16]: So, for me, that's a very, very material change in circumstances that merits another referendum on the question of independence, because one of the fundamental building blocks of the arguments against independence

677
00:49:14,877 --> 00:49:17,099
[SPEAKER_16]: was about the continuity of EU membership.

678
00:49:17,419 --> 00:49:18,120
[SPEAKER_16]: And we've lost that.

679
00:49:18,140 --> 00:49:26,928
[SPEAKER_16]: And people in Scotland are really suffering because of the absence of freedom of movement, the absence of access to the single market, the absence of access to the customs union.

680
00:49:27,108 --> 00:49:31,592
[SPEAKER_16]: All of these things are undermining our economy and our public services in Scotland.

681
00:49:32,053 --> 00:49:35,516
[SPEAKER_16]: And the sooner we can get back into the European Union, in my view, the better.

682
00:49:40,220 --> 00:49:41,021
[SPEAKER_33]: Let's take a question from Henry Cotton.

683
00:49:41,041 --> 00:49:41,982
[SPEAKER_33]: Henry Cotton.

684
00:49:43,632 --> 00:49:45,094
[SPEAKER_22]: There you are.

685
00:49:45,114 --> 00:49:47,498
[SPEAKER_22]: So Scotland's a world leader in renewable energy sources.

686
00:49:47,959 --> 00:49:49,882
[SPEAKER_22]: We look at the wind, marine power.

687
00:49:49,963 --> 00:49:53,949
[SPEAKER_22]: You have some of the best, if not the best, systems in the world.

688
00:49:54,811 --> 00:50:02,964
[SPEAKER_22]: Why is your government backtracking on the net zero promises and actually scrapping or going ahead with new oil licenses when you're such a world leader in renewable energy?

689
00:50:03,004 --> 00:50:05,809
[SPEAKER_22]: Why would you not double down on that as a nation?

690
00:50:05,907 --> 00:50:14,842
[SPEAKER_33]: So what you're actually saying is not quite that you're approving them, but you're saying you're going to judge whether or not they are compatible with your climate change goals, is that right?

691
00:50:14,943 --> 00:50:25,080
[SPEAKER_16]: Yes, and that's always been our position, that any new licences have got to pass a climate compatibility assessment before they could be approved, and that's got to be a rigorous process.

692
00:50:25,060 --> 00:50:26,242
[SPEAKER_33]: So how will that work, then?

693
00:50:26,262 --> 00:50:33,213
[SPEAKER_33]: Because you've got the Climate Change Committee saying expansion of fossil fuel production is not in line with net zero.

694
00:50:33,454 --> 00:50:45,433
[SPEAKER_33]: You've got global scientists, or scientists the world over, saying there is no way that you can have new oil wells, new gas drilling that is compatible with our climate change goals, and the Paris Agreement.

695
00:50:45,693 --> 00:50:46,815
[SPEAKER_33]: How do you think they can work?

696
00:50:46,795 --> 00:50:57,156
[SPEAKER_16]: I think the Committee on Climate Change would accept, or they do accept, that there will be a necessity to use fossil fuels, oil and gas for some time to come.

697
00:50:57,417 --> 00:51:01,045
[SPEAKER_33]: Existing, but they are certainly not recommending that we drill new oil wells.

698
00:51:01,065 --> 00:51:02,728
[SPEAKER_16]: But the question is,

699
00:51:02,708 --> 00:51:09,536
[SPEAKER_16]: we've got a multiplicity of issues to wrestle with here about energy security and about the journey to net zero.

700
00:51:09,856 --> 00:51:16,184
[SPEAKER_16]: The key point I would make is that the journey to net zero is absolutely inescapable.

701
00:51:16,424 --> 00:51:18,627
[SPEAKER_16]: We've got to do it for the sake of the planet.

702
00:51:19,247 --> 00:51:29,920
[SPEAKER_16]: But the judgments we've got to make have got to be made on a case-by-case basis where we explore and examine whether any new activity could be compatible with our objectives on climate change.

703
00:51:30,180 --> 00:51:31,922
[SPEAKER_33]: So give me, for example, how it ever could be.

704
00:51:31,902 --> 00:51:43,884
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, if, for example, it passed an assessment in relation to energy security and also in relation to the sourcing of alternative products, that might well be a justifiable case.

705
00:51:44,104 --> 00:51:48,612
[SPEAKER_16]: But that would have to be assessed rigorously in a climate compatibility assessment.

706
00:51:48,592 --> 00:51:51,316
[SPEAKER_16]: And when you say energy security, it would be sold on the open market.

707
00:51:51,336 --> 00:51:52,657
[SPEAKER_16]: It wouldn't make us any more secure, would it?

708
00:51:52,677 --> 00:52:02,090
[SPEAKER_16]: We're also taking into account all of the issues about the utilisation of that oil supply, if we use oil as an example.

709
00:52:02,110 --> 00:52:04,674
[SPEAKER_16]: So there would have to be a comprehensive assessment to do that.

710
00:52:05,675 --> 00:52:11,022
[SPEAKER_16]: Now, the Prime Minister has said that he would authorise 100 new oil and gas licences.

711
00:52:11,002 --> 00:52:13,225
[SPEAKER_16]: I think that's completely and utterly irresponsible.

712
00:52:13,606 --> 00:52:18,573
[SPEAKER_16]: It is essentially to deny the climate emergency and I would have nothing to do with that.

713
00:52:19,014 --> 00:52:36,520
[SPEAKER_16]: But what I do want to make sure is that we can work with the oil and gas sector to support it in making the transition to net zero because we will actually need lots of the skills in the oil and gas sector to be available to help us with the transition to net zero and that's a key part of how that agenda would be taken forward.

714
00:52:36,567 --> 00:52:42,513
[SPEAKER_22]: supporting that transition is actually saying, no, the line in the sand is here, we are not approving new licences.

715
00:52:43,034 --> 00:52:46,117
[SPEAKER_33]: Which is what your predecessor said, Nicola Sturgeon.

716
00:52:46,578 --> 00:52:51,243
[SPEAKER_16]: Essentially, we are putting a process in place to enable us to come to that judgment.

717
00:52:51,523 --> 00:52:57,870
[SPEAKER_16]: Throughout all of our analysis on this, we have said climate compatibility assessments are critical in that journey.

718
00:52:58,310 --> 00:53:01,073
[SPEAKER_16]: But I do want to stress the point of the importance

719
00:53:01,053 --> 00:53:09,625
[SPEAKER_16]: of maintaining the skills base which will help us to transition to net zero, because we will need those skills to help us in that journey.

720
00:53:09,645 --> 00:53:13,670
[SPEAKER_00]: Can you talk about the climate emergency?

721
00:53:13,810 --> 00:53:19,298
[SPEAKER_00]: What role will your government play in tackling the climate change, both in the UK and globally?

722
00:53:19,750 --> 00:53:34,088
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, we actually engage in a lot of dialogue with many Southern African countries, for example, about the loss and damage activity, where we became one of the first funders of a loss and damage program.

723
00:53:34,668 --> 00:53:38,113
[SPEAKER_16]: I had a meeting yesterday with the president of Zambia, who was in Edinburgh.

724
00:53:38,333 --> 00:53:47,344
[SPEAKER_16]: And we were discussing the developments of the Scottish-Zambia joint exchange program, which is heavily focused

725
00:53:47,324 --> 00:53:50,350
[SPEAKER_16]: on improving energy sustainability in Zambia.

726
00:53:50,410 --> 00:53:56,962
[SPEAKER_16]: It is part of the lost damage work that we are undertaking and also part of the international partnership work that we take forward.

727
00:53:57,623 --> 00:54:06,700
[SPEAKER_16]: I accept we have a domestic responsibility for tackling climate change and net zero, but I also accept that we have a responsibility to reach to other countries

728
00:54:06,680 --> 00:54:18,382
[SPEAKER_16]: and to work with them and to support them, given the fact that as a developed Western European country, we've created our fair share of the damage to the planet and we've got to address that in the loss and damage programmes with others.

729
00:54:18,743 --> 00:54:21,428
[SPEAKER_16]: Christina Rivas Graver, you've got a question.

730
00:54:22,310 --> 00:54:29,143
[SPEAKER_35]: Which Westminster leader would be the better choice for Scotland, Keir Starmer or Ishii Tsunak?

731
00:54:30,271 --> 00:54:32,937
[SPEAKER_16]: Come on, John, just answer that one.

732
00:54:33,498 --> 00:54:36,365
[SPEAKER_16]: You're asking me a very controversial question.

733
00:54:36,405 --> 00:54:39,492
[SPEAKER_42]: And we can't wait to hear your answer, can we, Christina?

734
00:54:39,512 --> 00:54:40,715
[SPEAKER_16]: And you're going to get an answer.

735
00:54:40,996 --> 00:54:45,225
[SPEAKER_16]: Look, I think the Conservative government's been a total disaster and a calamity.

736
00:54:45,325 --> 00:54:48,212
[SPEAKER_16]: So it can't be out of office quick enough, in my view.

737
00:54:54,200 --> 00:55:11,687
[SPEAKER_16]: I think it's an absolute racing certainty that the Labour Party will win the election in England, and I hope people in Scotland will recognise the importance of having strong SNP voices in the House of Commons who will argue for decisions to be made in Scotland for Scotland, and that will put the interests of people in Scotland first.

738
00:55:14,852 --> 00:55:15,673
[SPEAKER_33]: You did get an answer?

739
00:55:15,693 --> 00:55:16,935
[SPEAKER_33]: I did, yes.

740
00:55:16,975 --> 00:55:17,876
[SPEAKER_33]: Make a note of that.

741
00:55:18,057 --> 00:55:19,218
[SPEAKER_33]: I've got about two or three minutes left.

742
00:55:19,238 --> 00:55:20,961
[SPEAKER_33]: Anyone else got a question for John Swinney?

743
00:55:20,981 --> 00:55:22,924
[SPEAKER_33]: Yes, you then, in a certain time.

744
00:55:23,174 --> 00:55:32,637
[SPEAKER_09]: First Minister John Sweeney, my question is about the threat of independence and how that brings two countries apart essentially.

745
00:55:33,339 --> 00:55:41,098
[SPEAKER_09]: Would devolution of powers be something, devolution of powers to a bigger extent, would that be an option instead of full independence of Scotland?

746
00:55:41,197 --> 00:55:46,562
[SPEAKER_16]: over my political life, a number of powers have been devolved to the Scottish Parliament.

747
00:55:46,582 --> 00:55:48,304
[SPEAKER_16]: When I was born, the Scottish Parliament didn't exist.

748
00:55:48,584 --> 00:55:50,766
[SPEAKER_16]: I was one of the founding members of it 25 years ago.

749
00:55:51,307 --> 00:55:54,970
[SPEAKER_16]: So I've welcomed the development of that Scottish Parliament.

750
00:55:55,371 --> 00:56:00,816
[SPEAKER_16]: I was also part of a commission that secured more powers for the Scottish Parliament in 2016.

751
00:56:00,876 --> 00:56:02,918
[SPEAKER_16]: So we've strengthened the powers of the Parliament.

752
00:56:02,958 --> 00:56:07,963
[SPEAKER_16]: So I'm never going to say no to more powers for the Scottish Parliament.

753
00:56:07,943 --> 00:56:13,410
[SPEAKER_16]: But what I want to be able to do is to do the things that will transform people's lives.

754
00:56:13,691 --> 00:56:16,795
[SPEAKER_16]: I want to live in a fairer, more equal country.

755
00:56:16,875 --> 00:56:27,069
[SPEAKER_16]: I want to live in a country that prioritises the improvement of our economy and strengthening the rights and the responsibilities of people in our country.

756
00:56:27,429 --> 00:56:37,022
[SPEAKER_16]: And I don't think that can be achieved for us in the United Kingdom, which is why I want Scotland to be like Denmark or Ireland or Sweden, as an independent country,

757
00:56:37,002 --> 00:56:43,569
[SPEAKER_16]: And when you look at those countries, they are more prosperous, they're more equal, they're fairer than Scotland and the United Kingdom.

758
00:56:43,930 --> 00:56:48,835
[SPEAKER_16]: And that's a prize that I think people in Scotland are attracted to and want to make sure happens for our country.

759
00:56:49,196 --> 00:56:52,179
[SPEAKER_33]: OK. John Swinney, that's your half hour.

760
00:56:52,199 --> 00:56:54,642
[SPEAKER_33]: You've answered most of the questions, I think.

761
00:56:54,662 --> 00:56:55,964
[SPEAKER_33]: Maybe not all, I wouldn't say.

762
00:56:56,284 --> 00:56:57,625
[SPEAKER_33]: But can you please thank John Swinney?

763
00:57:05,715 --> 00:57:06,115
[SPEAKER_33]: So...

764
00:57:07,343 --> 00:57:08,344
[SPEAKER_33]: OK, we're halfway through.

765
00:57:08,685 --> 00:57:11,789
[SPEAKER_33]: Before we welcome Keir Starmer, I just got to quickly tell you what is happening next week.

766
00:57:11,809 --> 00:57:17,376
[SPEAKER_33]: So, on Monday, there'll be a Question Time Leader Special from Wales with Plaid Cymru leader Rhian Ap Iorwerth.

767
00:57:17,396 --> 00:57:21,240
[SPEAKER_33]: That's on BBC One Wales, the news channel and iPlayer, 7 o'clock.

768
00:57:21,581 --> 00:57:27,428
[SPEAKER_33]: Then, next Thursday, we've got the normal Question Time with the panel, desk and chairs from Birmingham.

769
00:57:27,408 --> 00:57:30,252
[SPEAKER_33]: We're particularly looking for first-time voters in that audience.

770
00:57:30,272 --> 00:57:32,576
[SPEAKER_33]: If that's you, go to the website and apply.

771
00:57:32,596 --> 00:57:35,380
[SPEAKER_33]: And then finally, the following night, also in Birmingham...

772
00:57:35,400 --> 00:57:38,164
[SPEAKER_33]: I tell you, you cannot move for Question Time next week.

773
00:57:38,224 --> 00:57:49,702
[SPEAKER_33]: The following night in Birmingham, we have yet another Question Time special, much like tonight, but it will be with the Green Party co-leader Adrian Ramsey and Reform UK's leader Nigel Farage, and that will be on at eight o'clock.

774
00:57:49,722 --> 00:57:51,745
[SPEAKER_33]: So if you want to be...

775
00:57:51,725 --> 00:57:53,448
[SPEAKER_33]: Interesting noises from the audience here.

776
00:57:54,049 --> 00:57:56,753
[SPEAKER_33]: If you want to be in that audience, go to the website as well.

777
00:57:57,093 --> 00:57:57,794
[SPEAKER_33]: OK, that's it.

778
00:57:57,995 --> 00:57:59,817
[SPEAKER_33]: All of our question time next week, back to tonight.

779
00:57:59,938 --> 00:58:00,779
[SPEAKER_33]: On to our next guest.

780
00:58:00,939 --> 00:58:04,925
[SPEAKER_33]: Would you please welcome the leader of the Labour Party, Sir Keir Starmer.

781
00:58:16,663 --> 00:58:17,164
[SPEAKER_17]: APPLAUSE Good to see you.

782
00:58:17,184 --> 00:58:17,645
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you very much.

783
00:58:17,665 --> 00:58:17,985
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

784
00:58:19,467 --> 00:58:20,288
[SPEAKER_33]: Okey-dokey.

785
00:58:20,328 --> 00:58:23,453
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, let me just remind you of the sort of general rules, Kirsten.

786
00:58:23,473 --> 00:58:24,535
[SPEAKER_33]: We're very pleased to have you here.

787
00:58:24,795 --> 00:58:25,556
[SPEAKER_33]: Thank you for having me.

788
00:58:25,576 --> 00:58:30,163
[SPEAKER_33]: Your job, obviously, is to answer the question, reasonably brief, if you would.

789
00:58:30,563 --> 00:58:33,408
[SPEAKER_33]: And if you don't, clearly, my job here is to keep you to the point.

790
00:58:33,428 --> 00:58:36,733
[SPEAKER_33]: So, let's kick off with our first one, which is from Emma Mitchell.

791
00:58:38,095 --> 00:58:39,216
[SPEAKER_36]: Good evening, Sir Keir.

792
00:58:40,458 --> 00:58:47,128
[SPEAKER_36]: You criticise the Tory manifesto as Jeremy Corbyn-like, anything you want can go in it,

793
00:58:47,463 --> 00:58:48,444
[SPEAKER_36]: nothing is costed.

794
00:58:49,326 --> 00:58:52,951
[SPEAKER_36]: Why did you back his original manifesto in 2019 then?

795
00:58:53,071 --> 00:58:59,440
[SPEAKER_27]: In 2019 I campaigned for the Labour Party, as I've always campaigned for the Labour Party.

796
00:59:00,121 --> 00:59:03,306
[SPEAKER_27]: I wanted good colleagues to be returned to Parliament.

797
00:59:03,927 --> 00:59:08,914
[SPEAKER_27]: I knew we had a job and a half to do as a Labour Party because I didn't think we were going to win that election.

798
00:59:09,130 --> 00:59:16,786
[SPEAKER_27]: Afterwards, because we got the worst results since 1935, the electorate clearly gave their verdict to us.

799
00:59:16,806 --> 00:59:20,654
[SPEAKER_27]: And we did a lot of work on how we needed to change the party.

800
00:59:21,175 --> 00:59:23,740
[SPEAKER_27]: And that started with what went wrong.

801
00:59:24,261 --> 00:59:29,873
[SPEAKER_27]: And in all the analysis we did, people said they quite liked some of what was in our manifesto.

802
00:59:29,853 --> 00:59:31,075
[SPEAKER_27]: But they thought it was too much.

803
00:59:31,596 --> 00:59:35,322
[SPEAKER_27]: And they wanted to see something which was fully costed and fully funded.

804
00:59:35,702 --> 00:59:41,231
[SPEAKER_27]: And that's why my manifesto going forward to this election is fully costed, fully funded.

805
00:59:41,612 --> 00:59:46,980
[SPEAKER_27]: Everything that we say we're going to do, we say how much it's going to be and where the money is coming from.

806
00:59:47,201 --> 00:59:50,005
[SPEAKER_27]: Because that's the sort of stability that we need.

807
00:59:49,985 --> 00:59:59,013
[SPEAKER_27]: The other thing that's obviously happened since then is Liz Truss put forward a number of unfunded commitments, in her case, tax cuts, and look what it did to the economy.

808
00:59:59,293 --> 01:00:04,658
[SPEAKER_27]: And there will be people in this audience, people who are watching, who are still paying the price for that.

809
01:00:04,938 --> 01:00:10,123
[SPEAKER_27]: And I said it about Rishi Sunak's manifesto, because he's now included unfunded commitments in that.

810
01:00:10,143 --> 01:00:11,885
[SPEAKER_27]: So he's repeating the mistake.

811
01:00:12,185 --> 01:00:14,046
[SPEAKER_27]: That is a political point going into an election.

812
01:00:14,066 --> 01:00:15,208
[SPEAKER_27]: I grant you that.

813
01:00:15,588 --> 01:00:19,131
[SPEAKER_27]: But it is also really important, because if you lose control of the economy,

814
01:00:19,111 --> 01:00:21,535
[SPEAKER_27]: It's ordinary people, working people who pay the price.

815
01:00:21,755 --> 01:00:24,379
[SPEAKER_27]: So many people, for example, still pay more on their mortgages.

816
01:00:24,399 --> 01:00:25,801
[SPEAKER_42]: OK, I suspect we're going to get on to that.

817
01:00:25,882 --> 01:00:36,799
[SPEAKER_27]: But that's why I said it, because I think it was overloaded, it wasn't fully funded, and I think that, particularly now, in 2024, the base camp, the foundation, is economic stability.

818
01:00:37,059 --> 01:00:37,319
[SPEAKER_33]: Thank you.

819
01:00:37,440 --> 01:00:44,350
[SPEAKER_33]: Can I just remind you, because you backed that manifesto, you also said in February 2019 that Jeremy Corbyn would make a great Prime Minister.

820
01:00:44,631 --> 01:00:47,295
[SPEAKER_33]: Now, you said already you thought you were going to win that election.

821
01:00:47,275 --> 01:00:50,379
[SPEAKER_33]: But putting that to one side, you said he would make a great Prime Minister.

822
01:00:50,599 --> 01:00:53,142
[SPEAKER_33]: Did you mean it, or did you have your fingers crossed behind your back?

823
01:00:53,262 --> 01:00:55,004
[SPEAKER_33]: Look, I didn't think we would...

824
01:00:55,024 --> 01:00:56,526
[SPEAKER_33]: I didn't think we would win that election.

825
01:00:56,546 --> 01:00:57,067
[SPEAKER_33]: You said that.

826
01:00:57,107 --> 01:01:00,591
[SPEAKER_33]: But irrespective of that, you said he'd make a great Prime Minister.

827
01:01:00,671 --> 01:01:01,372
[SPEAKER_27]: Did you mean it?

828
01:01:01,572 --> 01:01:05,637
[SPEAKER_27]: It wasn't a question that really arose because I didn't think we were going to win the election.

829
01:01:05,858 --> 01:01:06,498
[SPEAKER_27]: And now...

830
01:01:06,518 --> 01:01:07,420
[SPEAKER_33]: But we all heard you.

831
01:01:07,980 --> 01:01:10,223
[SPEAKER_33]: We all heard you saying he would be a great Prime Minister.

832
01:01:10,243 --> 01:01:12,646
[SPEAKER_33]: That was your way of telling the people here, vote for him.

833
01:01:12,986 --> 01:01:13,907
[SPEAKER_33]: Did you not mean that?

834
01:01:14,068 --> 01:01:16,050
[SPEAKER_33]: I was campaigning for the Labour Party.

835
01:01:16,030 --> 01:01:17,211
[SPEAKER_27]: And I'm glad I did.

836
01:01:17,391 --> 01:01:21,055
[SPEAKER_33]: But you also campaigned for Jeremy Corbyn to be prime minister.

837
01:01:21,075 --> 01:01:22,876
[SPEAKER_27]: I was campaigning for the Labour Party.

838
01:01:22,896 --> 01:01:23,997
[SPEAKER_27]: I was a Labour politician.

839
01:01:24,357 --> 01:01:28,561
[SPEAKER_27]: I wanted to be elected or re-elected, and I wanted good colleagues to be re-elected.

840
01:01:28,581 --> 01:01:29,362
[SPEAKER_27]: Just answer this, then.

841
01:01:29,382 --> 01:01:35,307
[SPEAKER_27]: Some of the people around the shadow cabinet table were people whose seats were saved because we campaigned hard for the Labour Party.

842
01:01:35,407 --> 01:01:37,409
[SPEAKER_33]: Just answer this, yes or no.

843
01:01:37,429 --> 01:01:40,452
[SPEAKER_33]: When you said Jeremy Corbyn would make a good prime minister, did you mean it?

844
01:01:40,972 --> 01:01:42,754
[SPEAKER_33]: Look, he would be a better prime minister.

845
01:01:42,794 --> 01:01:46,037
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, look what we got, Boris Johnson.

846
01:01:46,017 --> 01:01:50,284
[SPEAKER_27]: A man who made massive promises, didn't keep them, and then had to leave Parliament in disgrace.

847
01:01:50,304 --> 01:01:51,306
[SPEAKER_27]: OK, you're still not answering the question.

848
01:01:51,526 --> 01:01:55,452
[SPEAKER_33]: Did you think he'd make a great, not even just a good, a great Prime Minister?

849
01:01:55,572 --> 01:01:57,896
[SPEAKER_33]: I didn't think we were in a position to win that election.

850
01:01:57,916 --> 01:02:00,540
[SPEAKER_33]: And the more I look at the preparation we've now done... That's not an answer.

851
01:02:00,560 --> 01:02:04,407
[SPEAKER_27]: The more I look at the preparation we've now done, the more convinced I am about that.

852
01:02:04,427 --> 01:02:05,288
[SPEAKER_33]: Emma, where are you?

853
01:02:05,929 --> 01:02:06,490
[SPEAKER_33]: What do you think of that?

854
01:02:07,347 --> 01:02:08,209
[SPEAKER_36]: I'm not convinced.

855
01:02:08,890 --> 01:02:14,681
[SPEAKER_36]: It leaves me with the same question about integrity and trust that I had with the clown called Boris Johnson.

856
01:02:15,622 --> 01:02:19,069
[SPEAKER_36]: Now, don't hold back, Emma, obviously.

857
01:02:19,890 --> 01:02:22,495
[SPEAKER_36]: I would like to vote for someone that I can trust.

858
01:02:22,836 --> 01:02:24,218
[SPEAKER_33]: So you're undecided at the moment?

859
01:02:24,499 --> 01:02:25,761
[SPEAKER_36]: Yes, I am.

860
01:02:25,741 --> 01:02:30,345
[SPEAKER_33]: And has what you've heard from Keir Starmer persuaded you at all?

861
01:02:30,366 --> 01:02:32,568
[SPEAKER_33]: We've only just started, admittedly, but you asked that first question.

862
01:02:32,588 --> 01:02:34,229
[SPEAKER_36]: I might have to give him the next 20 minutes.

863
01:02:34,510 --> 01:02:36,552
[SPEAKER_33]: OK. All right, well, let's have another question, then.

864
01:02:37,072 --> 01:02:38,173
[SPEAKER_33]: Alastair McCall.

865
01:02:39,514 --> 01:02:39,995
[SPEAKER_33]: Where are you?

866
01:02:40,015 --> 01:02:41,737
[SPEAKER_33]: Because I've no idea where anyone's sitting.

867
01:02:41,757 --> 01:02:42,217
[SPEAKER_33]: Oh, sorry.

868
01:02:42,597 --> 01:02:43,058
[SPEAKER_23]: Good evening.

869
01:02:43,338 --> 01:02:52,407
[SPEAKER_23]: How can you increase spending in the NHS, the care system and defence when you have promised not to increase the mainstreams of taxation?

870
01:02:53,078 --> 01:02:56,122
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, in relation to taxation, I do need to be really clear.

871
01:02:56,162 --> 01:03:01,228
[SPEAKER_27]: We are not going to increase income tax, national insurance or VAT.

872
01:03:01,548 --> 01:03:12,221
[SPEAKER_27]: And the reason for that is because I think with the tax burden being as high as it is and a cost of living crisis, that is the wrong thing to do, particularly for working people.

873
01:03:12,241 --> 01:03:13,263
[SPEAKER_27]: So we're not going to do that.

874
01:03:13,603 --> 01:03:16,627
[SPEAKER_27]: We will put some immediate money into our public services.

875
01:03:16,827 --> 01:03:18,529
[SPEAKER_27]: I ran a public service for five years.

876
01:03:18,509 --> 01:03:33,548
[SPEAKER_27]: I believe in our public services and I know they need to be properly funded so we will put in money to the NHS straight away and the purpose of that will be to allow us to do 40,000 extra appointments and operations every week

877
01:03:33,528 --> 01:03:39,316
[SPEAKER_27]: That's 2 million a year extra appointments to bring the waiting list down, because it's nearly 8 million now and we've got to get it down.

878
01:03:39,336 --> 01:03:40,257
[SPEAKER_27]: And what about defence?

879
01:03:40,297 --> 01:03:44,883
[SPEAKER_27]: And that will allow the NHS to be properly, you know, to get back on its feet.

880
01:03:44,903 --> 01:03:46,385
[SPEAKER_27]: We'll have to then make it fit for the future.

881
01:03:46,726 --> 01:03:47,487
[SPEAKER_27]: And what about defence?

882
01:03:47,507 --> 01:03:48,428
[SPEAKER_27]: That's also in the question.

883
01:03:48,448 --> 01:03:50,932
[SPEAKER_27]: Where are you going to find the money for that if you don't increase streams of taxation?

884
01:03:50,952 --> 01:03:58,041
[SPEAKER_27]: Defence has to be the first priority of any government defending your country, and therefore we will always make the money available for defence.

885
01:03:58,101 --> 01:04:00,885
[SPEAKER_27]: And you can see at the moment we live in a particularly volatile

886
01:04:01,152 --> 01:04:01,733
[SPEAKER_27]: world.

887
01:04:01,873 --> 01:04:09,904
[SPEAKER_27]: So we will make the money available for defence, we will put that extra money into the NHS, and I want to see our public services running properly.

888
01:04:10,264 --> 01:04:21,439
[SPEAKER_27]: And my wife works in the NHS, my mum worked in the NHS, my sister worked in the NHS, and to see it in the state that it's in now, where I say it's on its knees, my wife says no it's not, it's flat on its face.

889
01:04:21,419 --> 01:04:23,081
[SPEAKER_27]: is a complete disgrace.

890
01:04:23,442 --> 01:04:32,775
[SPEAKER_27]: After 14 years of this government, we will have to pick it up, put it back on its feet, but also do something else, reform, to make sure that it's fit for the future.

891
01:04:33,096 --> 01:04:36,040
[SPEAKER_27]: That will require a different model, a preventative model.

892
01:04:36,060 --> 01:04:37,662
[SPEAKER_27]: I'll just give this one last example.

893
01:04:37,742 --> 01:04:40,226
[SPEAKER_27]: Very brief, if you want, because there are a lot of hands up.

894
01:04:40,246 --> 01:04:42,049
[SPEAKER_27]: I went to Alder Hey Children's Hospital.

895
01:04:42,089 --> 01:04:42,850
[SPEAKER_27]: Some people will know it.

896
01:04:42,870 --> 01:04:44,372
[SPEAKER_27]: It's a brilliant children's hospital.

897
01:04:44,673 --> 01:04:51,588
[SPEAKER_27]: in Liverpool, where I saw heart surgery, or the wards where they do it, on children aged 0-2.

898
01:04:51,649 --> 01:05:02,192
[SPEAKER_27]: It was very humbling and uplifting, but I also discovered that the single most common reason that 6-10 year olds are admitted to the children's hospital there, same across the country,

899
01:05:02,375 --> 01:05:06,001
[SPEAKER_27]: is to have their teeth taken out because of teeth decay.

900
01:05:06,021 --> 01:05:08,025
[SPEAKER_27]: That is a complete and utter disgrace.

901
01:05:08,045 --> 01:05:10,890
[SPEAKER_27]: So we need to move the model and change the model for the NHS as well.

902
01:05:11,110 --> 01:05:11,371
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you.

903
01:05:11,391 --> 01:05:11,932
[SPEAKER_33]: I'm going to take this one.

904
01:05:11,952 --> 01:05:13,795
[SPEAKER_33]: Can I gently encourage you to move back?

905
01:05:13,815 --> 01:05:14,536
[SPEAKER_33]: To move back to it?

906
01:05:14,556 --> 01:05:16,780
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, just so that we can see you more clearly for the viewers at home.

907
01:05:16,800 --> 01:05:19,024
[SPEAKER_33]: It's like that box inside the pitch in football, isn't it?

908
01:05:19,044 --> 01:05:19,886
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, it's not that.

909
01:05:19,906 --> 01:05:21,929
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, you'd know, because obviously you play a lot of football.

910
01:05:22,050 --> 01:05:23,412
[SPEAKER_33]: But you're just better lit there.

911
01:05:23,432 --> 01:05:25,716
[SPEAKER_33]: So yes, person at the back in the pink top.

912
01:05:26,135 --> 01:05:30,190
[SPEAKER_15]: At the moment, tensions with Europe are at an all-time high.

913
01:05:31,194 --> 01:05:37,798
[SPEAKER_15]: With more and more right-wing governments in Europe, how are you going to negotiate that and make sure we have a safe relationship?

914
01:05:38,825 --> 01:05:59,787
[SPEAKER_27]: With Europe, I'm worried about some of the tendencies across Europe because I'm obviously leading a progressive party and I think that the answers to the problems we face globally, whether that's climate, whether that's conflict, whether that's extreme poverty, getting our economy going, are progressive answers to that.

915
01:06:00,087 --> 01:06:27,546
[SPEAKER_27]: Now, I will have to work, if I'm elected into government, with all leaders across Europe, but I will always make that progressive argument that, in the end, you have to stabilise your economy, you have to get investment in to make sure that we get the jobs of the future, we have to take our climate obligations seriously and not see them as just a sort of challenge that we don't want, but as a brilliant opportunity for the next generation of jobs and play our full part in descaling conflict.

916
01:06:27,526 --> 01:06:34,058
[SPEAKER_27]: If we're able to get over the line in two weeks' time, we have a platform for that, which is really important.

917
01:06:34,078 --> 01:06:39,608
[SPEAKER_27]: If you look across Europe, I am genuinely worried by some of the political trends and moves that we see.

918
01:06:39,649 --> 01:06:41,552
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you.

919
01:06:41,583 --> 01:06:44,066
[SPEAKER_31]: Sorry, I'm going to take it back to the NHS.

920
01:06:44,907 --> 01:06:48,711
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm a nurse and I work on a very busy surgical admissions unit.

921
01:06:49,552 --> 01:06:55,618
[SPEAKER_31]: You're going about the waiting list and everything, and putting money in, but how are we going to see that on the ward?

922
01:06:56,219 --> 01:07:05,389
[SPEAKER_31]: Because all I can see is we've got pressure all the time, and adding, say you're going to get rid of the waiting list, that's putting more pressure on the staff.

923
01:07:05,729 --> 01:07:08,552
[SPEAKER_31]: So what support are you going to give the staff on the ward?

924
01:07:08,532 --> 01:07:10,234
[SPEAKER_31]: so that you can treat more patients, that's your point?

925
01:07:10,254 --> 01:07:10,515
[SPEAKER_27]: Yes, yeah.

926
01:07:10,535 --> 01:07:13,479
[SPEAKER_27]: The first thing I'd say is, we treat you with respect.

927
01:07:14,340 --> 01:07:20,788
[SPEAKER_27]: And I say that because we have a Prime Minister who, 18 months or so ago, said, I'm going to get the waiting list down.

928
01:07:21,329 --> 01:07:23,432
[SPEAKER_27]: And he said, hold me personally responsible.

929
01:07:24,012 --> 01:07:26,175
[SPEAKER_27]: And now he hasn't got them down, because they've gone up and knocked down.

930
01:07:26,295 --> 01:07:26,876
[SPEAKER_27]: He blames you.

931
01:07:27,317 --> 01:07:28,498
[SPEAKER_27]: He blames the NHS staff.

932
01:07:28,518 --> 01:07:32,143
[SPEAKER_27]: We will never do that, because I know how hard you work all of the time.

933
01:07:32,123 --> 01:07:34,809
[SPEAKER_27]: in Covid in particular than the waiting list.

934
01:07:34,829 --> 01:07:37,234
[SPEAKER_27]: But we do have to take the pressure off the waiting list.

935
01:07:37,254 --> 01:07:38,657
[SPEAKER_27]: Now that is an ask of staff.

936
01:07:38,677 --> 01:07:39,498
[SPEAKER_27]: It is an ask of staff.

937
01:07:39,518 --> 01:07:45,571
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm not going to say otherwise because we will be working evenings and weekends to get those lists down.

938
01:07:45,811 --> 01:07:48,597
[SPEAKER_27]: It will help because all of the hospitals I've been

939
01:07:48,728 --> 01:07:52,677
[SPEAKER_27]: to say having that waiting list is a real drag on what else we can do.

940
01:07:52,718 --> 01:07:55,384
[SPEAKER_27]: We will work, we'll pay the staff properly to do it.

941
01:07:55,685 --> 01:08:05,067
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm convinced we can do it, by the way, because in St Thomas' in London and one of the Leeds hospitals I went to, I met the teams that are doing this already because they've decided

942
01:08:05,047 --> 01:08:09,254
[SPEAKER_27]: to do that?

943
01:08:10,335 --> 01:08:14,682
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't work in a big hospital in London or Leeds, I work in Shropshire.

944
01:08:16,004 --> 01:08:19,670
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't think we see that the same, we seem to get forgotten about more.

945
01:08:19,930 --> 01:08:22,414
[SPEAKER_33]: If you were asked to work in Shropshire, what would you do?

946
01:08:22,394 --> 01:08:27,721
[SPEAKER_33]: as the Shadow Health Secretary, is suggesting that you work extra hours in order to try and treat more patients.

947
01:08:27,921 --> 01:08:28,301
[SPEAKER_31]: Yeah.

948
01:08:28,321 --> 01:08:29,763
[SPEAKER_31]: You don't even pay for it.

949
01:08:30,044 --> 01:08:38,274
[SPEAKER_31]: If you got better pay, I mean, because at the minute all I see is it all goes on agency staff and the staff that are willing to get the pay and we don't get the pay.

950
01:08:38,294 --> 01:08:44,622
[SPEAKER_27]: I think there's a separate issue though, you're quite right, which is we need the workforce coming in so we don't use agency staff in the same way.

951
01:08:44,872 --> 01:08:55,404
[SPEAKER_27]: And that requires a workforce plan, which we've also got fully costed to come in to effectively be the cavalry that comes in and gives you the support you need on the front line.

952
01:08:55,424 --> 01:08:56,265
[SPEAKER_27]: But that will also take time, won't it?

953
01:08:56,285 --> 01:08:57,186
[SPEAKER_27]: It's going to take years.

954
01:08:57,306 --> 01:08:59,108
[SPEAKER_27]: It will take time, but let me just...

955
01:08:59,128 --> 01:08:59,809
[SPEAKER_27]: I mean, it'll take years.

956
01:08:59,849 --> 01:09:08,038
[SPEAKER_27]: Yeah, let me just deal with this, because I've been leader of the Labour Party now for four and a half years, and every year we've had a winter crisis in the NHS.

957
01:09:08,058 --> 01:09:10,120
[SPEAKER_27]: You'll be completely familiar with that.

958
01:09:10,100 --> 01:09:20,774
[SPEAKER_27]: And what we do is we put a sticking plaster on that in about January or February, it just about limps through to the summer, and then the only guarantee is you're going to have another one next year and it's going to be worse.

959
01:09:21,235 --> 01:09:27,403
[SPEAKER_27]: And everybody says, everything else will take too long, don't tell me things that are going to take three or four years, and nothing gets done.

960
01:09:27,423 --> 01:09:30,167
[SPEAKER_27]: So we go round and round in circles.

961
01:09:30,147 --> 01:09:40,606
[SPEAKER_27]: not fixing it, sticking plaster politics, is one of the biggest problems of politics now, which is politicians not being honest about how long it's actually going to take to fix things.

962
01:09:40,626 --> 01:09:41,768
[SPEAKER_27]: OK, well, be honest with us now.

963
01:09:42,008 --> 01:09:45,955
[SPEAKER_33]: If it's going to take time to train the staff, let's get started on training the staff now, not put it off.

964
01:09:45,975 --> 01:09:47,357
[SPEAKER_33]: We know how bad waiting lists are.

965
01:09:47,758 --> 01:09:47,979
[SPEAKER_33]: Yes.

966
01:09:48,079 --> 01:09:51,445
[SPEAKER_33]: And most of us are familiar with some of the problems of the NHS, because we all use it.

967
01:09:51,745 --> 01:09:54,450
[SPEAKER_33]: So when can the people here expect

968
01:09:54,430 --> 01:10:00,360
[SPEAKER_33]: to see an improvement in the NHS and be able to feel that they can get an appointment at least within a month, say.

969
01:10:00,400 --> 01:10:02,424
[SPEAKER_33]: Should we wait two years, three years, six months?

970
01:10:02,884 --> 01:10:08,334
[SPEAKER_27]: We will start the work on waiting lists on day one in government if we're elected into government.

971
01:10:08,354 --> 01:10:13,542
[SPEAKER_27]: I've set out the big things that we want to do in government, but also the things we'll do on day one, the first step.

972
01:10:13,562 --> 01:10:16,928
[SPEAKER_33]: And in terms of when we can expect to feel an improvement in the NHS,

973
01:10:16,908 --> 01:10:17,829
[SPEAKER_33]: How long should we wait?

974
01:10:17,849 --> 01:10:20,853
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, we'll get those operations going as quickly as we can with the staff.

975
01:10:20,933 --> 01:10:24,076
[SPEAKER_27]: We've got the models from the London Hospital, the Leeds Hospital.

976
01:10:24,257 --> 01:10:31,205
[SPEAKER_27]: We're asking those teams to go around the country to talk to other hospitals, maybe the one that you work in, to say, this is how we've done it.

977
01:10:31,725 --> 01:10:33,247
[SPEAKER_27]: This is what we would recommend.

978
01:10:33,548 --> 01:10:35,930
[SPEAKER_27]: Now, however long that takes, but we will get that.

979
01:10:35,950 --> 01:10:36,671
[SPEAKER_27]: How long will it take?

980
01:10:36,691 --> 01:10:39,274
[SPEAKER_27]: We will make a start on that absolutely straight away.

981
01:10:39,294 --> 01:10:39,975
[SPEAKER_27]: You've made that clear.

982
01:10:39,995 --> 01:10:44,200
[SPEAKER_27]: Everybody here will either be on a waiting list or know somebody who's on a waiting list.

983
01:10:44,220 --> 01:10:45,902
[SPEAKER_27]: It's incredibly discomforting.

984
01:10:45,882 --> 01:10:49,306
[SPEAKER_27]: And it means people aren't able to go to work, and that's not helping the economy.

985
01:10:49,326 --> 01:10:54,232
[SPEAKER_33]: You're making an appeal, and we all hear it and understand it, to be realistic about how long things take.

986
01:10:54,653 --> 01:10:56,315
[SPEAKER_33]: So your pledge is to get waiting lists down.

987
01:10:56,996 --> 01:11:02,142
[SPEAKER_33]: When can we expect waiting lists to come down to a reasonable level?

988
01:11:02,583 --> 01:11:05,206
[SPEAKER_27]: We will be able to do 2 million a year on this model.

989
01:11:05,687 --> 01:11:10,413
[SPEAKER_27]: That means that over the course of the Parliament, we'll get it down and clear the backlog completely.

990
01:11:10,793 --> 01:11:12,235
[SPEAKER_27]: By the end of the Parliament, that's your pledge?

991
01:11:12,255 --> 01:11:14,758
[SPEAKER_27]: Yeah, but hear me out, because this is difficult stuff.

992
01:11:14,738 --> 01:11:16,781
[SPEAKER_27]: We did it last time we were in power.

993
01:11:17,242 --> 01:11:24,833
[SPEAKER_27]: The Labour government then said, because the waiting list... You've all probably seen those charts where the waiting lists are through the roof when the Tories come out of government.

994
01:11:24,913 --> 01:11:26,676
[SPEAKER_27]: We then bring them down.

995
01:11:26,756 --> 01:11:31,283
[SPEAKER_33]: Also, Labour spent a lot more on the NHS then than you are pledging, but just to be clear.

996
01:11:31,303 --> 01:11:35,890
[SPEAKER_27]: We got the waiting list at the lowest ever level and the highest possible satisfaction in the NHS.

997
01:11:35,970 --> 01:11:37,412
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm really proud that we did it.

998
01:11:37,432 --> 01:11:40,177
[SPEAKER_27]: And if it were still there, we wouldn't be in the problem we are in this country.

999
01:11:40,217 --> 01:11:41,999
[SPEAKER_27]: OK, let me take another question.

1000
01:11:42,019 --> 01:11:42,400
[SPEAKER_27]: This woman here.

1001
01:11:42,953 --> 01:11:54,313
[SPEAKER_06]: With all of the backtracking on policies from Labour, especially around education and education fees for higher education, why should anybody believe that you'll produce a stable and trustworthy government?

1002
01:11:55,475 --> 01:12:00,303
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you for the question on tuition fees, and I'm really glad to get it, because... Well, it's not just about tuition fees.

1003
01:12:00,323 --> 01:12:00,784
[SPEAKER_33]: Hang on a minute.

1004
01:12:00,804 --> 01:12:01,465
[SPEAKER_27]: You said education fees.

1005
01:12:01,606 --> 01:12:03,509
[SPEAKER_33]: Yes, but you're also talking about U-turns generally, aren't you?

1006
01:12:03,529 --> 01:12:04,050
[SPEAKER_33]: Just generally.

1007
01:12:04,190 --> 01:12:07,416
[SPEAKER_33]: OK, so scrapping the two-child benefit cap.

1008
01:12:07,516 --> 01:12:08,377
[SPEAKER_33]: You're going to scrap tuition fees.

1009
01:12:08,397 --> 01:12:10,401
[SPEAKER_33]: You're going to nationalise mail, rail, energy and water services.

1010
01:12:10,421 --> 01:12:12,043
[SPEAKER_33]: You're going to have £28 billion a year for green industry.

1011
01:12:12,063 --> 01:12:12,685
[SPEAKER_33]: I mean, I could go on.

1012
01:12:12,705 --> 01:12:13,205
[SPEAKER_33]: I don't need to.

1013
01:12:13,546 --> 01:12:15,289
[SPEAKER_33]: It's about more than just education.

1014
01:12:15,269 --> 01:12:17,733
[SPEAKER_27]: Yeah, so let me address it straight on, tuition fees.

1015
01:12:18,675 --> 01:12:23,924
[SPEAKER_27]: Very expensive for students, don't work very well, students come out with a huge debt around their neck.

1016
01:12:24,485 --> 01:12:27,450
[SPEAKER_27]: And five years ago, I said, we should get rid of them.

1017
01:12:29,033 --> 01:12:30,696
[SPEAKER_27]: Now, five years down the line,

1018
01:12:31,013 --> 01:12:33,035
[SPEAKER_27]: The economy's been very badly damaged.

1019
01:12:33,556 --> 01:12:36,039
[SPEAKER_27]: We don't have the money to do everything we want to do.

1020
01:12:36,380 --> 01:12:37,801
[SPEAKER_27]: We do need to change the tuition fees.

1021
01:12:38,362 --> 01:12:51,418
[SPEAKER_27]: But I had a choice to make, which was, of the available money, do I use it for getting rid of tuition fees, which would help students, I accept that because I know how hard it is, or do I use that money to get our waiting list out?

1022
01:12:51,398 --> 01:12:53,321
[SPEAKER_27]: That's a political decision that I took.

1023
01:12:53,861 --> 01:12:59,770
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm not going to do the tuition fees abolition because I want to put that money to get our NHS back on its feet.

1024
01:13:00,010 --> 01:13:00,951
[SPEAKER_27]: That is my decision.

1025
01:13:01,052 --> 01:13:02,253
[SPEAKER_27]: It's a political decision.

1026
01:13:02,534 --> 01:13:07,481
[SPEAKER_27]: I accept it's different to the position I put forward five years ago when the damage hadn't been done to the economy.

1027
01:13:07,761 --> 01:13:12,748
[SPEAKER_27]: But that's the position because I don't think until we get those waiting lists down we can

1028
01:13:12,998 --> 01:13:17,384
[SPEAKER_27]: afford to do the tuition fees as well, so we had to make a choice about it.

1029
01:13:17,424 --> 01:13:18,585
[SPEAKER_27]: And it's a straight choice.

1030
01:13:18,605 --> 01:13:20,968
[SPEAKER_27]: And, you know, I'm saying this to you before the election.

1031
01:13:21,269 --> 01:13:28,578
[SPEAKER_27]: If you think that waiting lists down is more important than getting rid of tuition fees, if that's the right choice, then you'll go along with me.

1032
01:13:28,618 --> 01:13:38,411
[SPEAKER_27]: If you say, no, I'd rather the waiting list stayed where they were, bad luck to all the people on the waiting list, but at least students aren't paying fees, that's a different choice, not the one I would take.

1033
01:13:38,831 --> 01:13:41,875
[SPEAKER_27]: The other example you put to me is nationalising energy.

1034
01:13:42,361 --> 01:13:52,773
[SPEAKER_27]: When we had the energy crisis two years ago, when everybody's prices went through the roof, both at home and in their businesses, I asked my team to mock up what the options were.

1035
01:13:53,474 --> 01:13:55,176
[SPEAKER_27]: One option was nationalising energy.

1036
01:13:55,917 --> 01:13:58,000
[SPEAKER_27]: That would have cost tens of billions of pounds.

1037
01:13:58,520 --> 01:14:02,965
[SPEAKER_27]: That money would have been spent on shareholders to buy them off.

1038
01:14:02,985 --> 01:14:05,128
[SPEAKER_27]: And not a penny could have been used to lower the bills.

1039
01:14:05,682 --> 01:14:15,909
[SPEAKER_27]: The alternative was a windfall tax on oil and gas companies to cap the bills of many people in this room and across the country, and to ensure that people actually survived through the last two years.

1040
01:14:16,109 --> 01:14:16,992
[SPEAKER_27]: I took the second choice.

1041
01:14:17,453 --> 01:14:21,784
[SPEAKER_27]: I don't think I could have stood here today and say, I didn't do anything about your bills, sorry about that.

1042
01:14:21,764 --> 01:14:26,472
[SPEAKER_27]: You've all had to pay a fortune, but I did pay off the shareholders and nationalise energy.

1043
01:14:26,632 --> 01:14:28,235
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm a common-sense politician.

1044
01:14:28,535 --> 01:14:33,964
[SPEAKER_27]: I work through the issues, and to me, it did not make sense to nationalise energy and not get the bills down.

1045
01:14:33,984 --> 01:14:36,007
[SPEAKER_27]: So I decided we should go for getting the bills down.

1046
01:14:36,068 --> 01:14:37,270
[SPEAKER_27]: They are political choices.

1047
01:14:37,550 --> 01:14:41,757
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm telling you what they are before the election, and people can then make their mind up according to what they think.

1048
01:14:41,777 --> 01:14:43,259
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, that's what our audience here will be doing.

1049
01:14:43,299 --> 01:14:45,443
[SPEAKER_33]: Let's hear the question from Susan Purdy's.

1050
01:14:47,448 --> 01:14:48,570
[SPEAKER_33]: Is that you, Susan?

1051
01:14:48,590 --> 01:14:49,312
[SPEAKER_33]: Oh, that's you.

1052
01:14:50,474 --> 01:15:04,020
[SPEAKER_32]: Given your severe criticism of the Conservatives on the topic of immigration, do you think it's acceptable at this point, so near the general election, for your own party not to commit to specific targets around this critical topic?

1053
01:15:04,040 --> 01:15:05,523
[SPEAKER_33]: And you're talking about overall migration?

1054
01:15:05,543 --> 01:15:06,064
[SPEAKER_33]: Yes.

1055
01:15:06,466 --> 01:15:11,935
[SPEAKER_27]: Yeah, look, migration is at record levels at the moment under this government.

1056
01:15:12,617 --> 01:15:14,300
[SPEAKER_27]: They've completely lost control.

1057
01:15:14,360 --> 01:15:15,602
[SPEAKER_27]: We need to get that number down.

1058
01:15:16,103 --> 01:15:17,886
[SPEAKER_27]: We need to get it significantly down.

1059
01:15:18,447 --> 01:15:26,140
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm not going to put an arbitrary figure on it, because every single politician who's put a number on it has never met that number.

1060
01:15:26,821 --> 01:15:27,843
[SPEAKER_27]: But we need to get it down.

1061
01:15:28,184 --> 01:15:29,265
[SPEAKER_27]: We need to get it down.

1062
01:15:29,626 --> 01:15:31,950
[SPEAKER_27]: You're asking, is that a reason not to do it?

1063
01:15:32,352 --> 01:15:34,134
[SPEAKER_27]: We want to get it down significantly.

1064
01:15:34,394 --> 01:15:39,219
[SPEAKER_27]: It needs to be balanced immigration so that it works for our economy and works for our country.

1065
01:15:39,520 --> 01:15:40,261
[SPEAKER_27]: We need to get it down.

1066
01:15:40,461 --> 01:15:43,584
[SPEAKER_27]: But if we're going to do that, we need to understand what the problem is.

1067
01:15:44,025 --> 01:15:47,408
[SPEAKER_27]: And the problem at the moment is we haven't got the skills that we need in this country.

1068
01:15:47,689 --> 01:15:49,811
[SPEAKER_27]: So many, many people are coming on work visas.

1069
01:15:50,091 --> 01:15:57,980
[SPEAKER_27]: So we need a skills strategy to ensure that we have the skills in this country to ensure that the workforce is available here for the jobs that we need doing.

1070
01:15:58,280 --> 01:16:01,043
[SPEAKER_27]: One specific example is social care.

1071
01:16:01,023 --> 01:16:06,098
[SPEAKER_27]: Many people coming here are coming into social care and working hard in social care, by the way.

1072
01:16:06,539 --> 01:16:10,330
[SPEAKER_27]: But that's because we haven't got a plan for the staff within social care.

1073
01:16:10,350 --> 01:16:11,634
[SPEAKER_27]: They're all fragmented.

1074
01:16:11,654 --> 01:16:13,058
[SPEAKER_27]: My sister's a care worker.

1075
01:16:13,274 --> 01:16:18,962
[SPEAKER_27]: They're on fragmented contracts, poor terms and conditions, and many of them leave.

1076
01:16:19,462 --> 01:16:26,372
[SPEAKER_27]: Most of them leaving social care go to work in the NHS, because they've got a better framework for pay and poor progression.

1077
01:16:26,652 --> 01:16:31,699
[SPEAKER_27]: So we've got a problem we need to fix here, and we would have a fair pay agreement for all the workers.

1078
01:16:31,719 --> 01:16:35,704
[SPEAKER_33]: In fairness, we're getting away from having a target on migration numbers.

1079
01:16:35,684 --> 01:16:52,140
[SPEAKER_33]: If you are not going to set any kind of target, how can you know that the plans you're putting in place, for example, building something like 300,000 houses a year, or how many staff you want to have in the NHS, if you don't know how many people you're anticipating having in the country, how can you possibly know that you're planning correctly?

1080
01:16:52,561 --> 01:16:55,984
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, we want to get the number down, so we'll see if that number is coming down.

1081
01:16:56,004 --> 01:17:05,674
[SPEAKER_33]: You've made that point, but if you have literally no idea, or not that you're going to share with us anyway, of how many people you think is a sensible number to have coming into the country and staying here,

1082
01:17:06,059 --> 01:17:07,743
[SPEAKER_33]: invited in on visa, whatever it might be.

1083
01:17:08,124 --> 01:17:10,249
[SPEAKER_33]: How can you possibly plan for our public services?

1084
01:17:10,350 --> 01:17:16,845
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, we've got a plan for our social care workforce with a fair pay agreement so that we retain the good people we've got working in care.

1085
01:17:17,307 --> 01:17:20,013
[SPEAKER_27]: We've got a plan for construction, for example, to build those houses.

1086
01:17:20,073 --> 01:17:23,241
[SPEAKER_27]: But how do you know it'll be the right number of houses if you don't know how many people will live here?

1087
01:17:23,913 --> 01:17:29,018
[SPEAKER_27]: But we need 1.5 million houses because too many people are waiting for a house that they want to live in.

1088
01:17:29,919 --> 01:17:32,642
[SPEAKER_27]: The dream of home ownership is real for so many people.

1089
01:17:32,662 --> 01:17:34,324
[SPEAKER_27]: They want to own their own home.

1090
01:17:34,604 --> 01:17:40,130
[SPEAKER_27]: The average age now for somebody to get on the housing ladder is 36 or 37.

1091
01:17:40,530 --> 01:17:45,235
[SPEAKER_27]: It is impossible or near on impossible for young people to get their first home.

1092
01:17:45,255 --> 01:17:47,037
[SPEAKER_27]: We have to build more houses.

1093
01:17:47,398 --> 01:17:49,880
[SPEAKER_27]: That means we have to take tough decisions on things like planning.

1094
01:17:50,100 --> 01:17:52,603
[SPEAKER_27]: I was at housing development here just in Outer York

1095
01:17:52,583 --> 01:18:03,041
[SPEAKER_27]: this morning, 650 houses being bought by locals, but it took 15 years from the plans being submitted to the houses being built.

1096
01:18:03,061 --> 01:18:04,804
[SPEAKER_33]: We are far off migration targets.

1097
01:18:04,964 --> 01:18:07,990
[SPEAKER_33]: Forgive me, but we are well off the target now.

1098
01:18:08,110 --> 01:18:13,018
[SPEAKER_33]: I appreciate you have the message you want to put out, but we also need to directly answer the questions being put by the audience.

1099
01:18:13,319 --> 01:18:14,581
[SPEAKER_33]: Kate Collins, whereabouts are you?

1100
01:18:16,464 --> 01:18:17,005
[SPEAKER_41]: Hi, Keir.

1101
01:18:17,727 --> 01:18:24,383
[SPEAKER_41]: Three years ago, you criticised your MP, Rosie Duffield, for saying only women have a cervix.

1102
01:18:24,984 --> 01:18:26,608
[SPEAKER_41]: You recently backtracked on this.

1103
01:18:27,450 --> 01:18:31,720
[SPEAKER_41]: What do you believe now and how do we know that you will stick to your views?

1104
01:18:31,852 --> 01:18:35,916
[SPEAKER_33]: So, Rosie Duffield said in 2020, only women have a cervix.

1105
01:18:37,017 --> 01:18:39,799
[SPEAKER_33]: You said in response, that's something that shouldn't be said, it's not right.

1106
01:18:40,080 --> 01:18:48,568
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, look, on the biology, I agree with what Tony Blair said the other day in relation to men having penises and women having vaginas.

1107
01:18:49,148 --> 01:18:50,049
[SPEAKER_27]: But what I will say is...

1108
01:18:50,069 --> 01:18:51,350
[SPEAKER_27]: So, you've changed your position?

1109
01:18:51,530 --> 01:18:55,754
[SPEAKER_27]: Just, on the biology, that doesn't help on the gender.

1110
01:18:55,774 --> 01:18:59,698
[SPEAKER_27]: There are some people who don't identify with the gender that they're born into.

1111
01:18:59,678 --> 01:19:04,966
[SPEAKER_27]: And they go through a lot of anxiety and distress.

1112
01:19:05,527 --> 01:19:13,459
[SPEAKER_27]: And my view in life is to respect and give dignity to everyone, whatever their position.

1113
01:19:14,221 --> 01:19:15,763
[SPEAKER_27]: And I will always do that.

1114
01:19:15,743 --> 01:19:28,845
[SPEAKER_27]: And I was worried at the time, and you referenced that particular debate, by the way in which the debate was being conducted, because it got very toxic, very divided, very hard line, and we lost sight of people in that.

1115
01:19:29,245 --> 01:19:42,207
[SPEAKER_27]: So much so that that drags you to a place where we end up, as we did end up, with the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom making a trans joke in Parliament

1116
01:19:42,710 --> 01:19:46,825
[SPEAKER_27]: when the mother of a murdered trans teenager was watching on.

1117
01:19:47,327 --> 01:19:51,161
[SPEAKER_27]: That is a shocking place to get to.

1118
01:19:51,181 --> 01:19:52,365
[SPEAKER_41]: You want to come back in?

1119
01:19:53,155 --> 01:19:57,279
[SPEAKER_41]: So, the question is actually alluding to tolerance as well.

1120
01:19:57,679 --> 01:19:57,779
[SPEAKER_41]: Yeah.

1121
01:19:57,799 --> 01:19:59,280
[SPEAKER_41]: And having tolerance of differing views.

1122
01:19:59,320 --> 01:20:01,623
[SPEAKER_41]: And I do appreciate the comments you've made.

1123
01:20:02,223 --> 01:20:07,548
[SPEAKER_41]: However, how are you going to deal with when people in your party are going to come up against you?

1124
01:20:07,668 --> 01:20:08,969
[SPEAKER_41]: It's likely you're going to be in government.

1125
01:20:09,449 --> 01:20:11,171
[SPEAKER_41]: Who knows if you'll have a supermajority?

1126
01:20:11,211 --> 01:20:18,077
[SPEAKER_41]: And, as John Swinney actually mentioned earlier, politics can become polarised.

1127
01:20:18,738 --> 01:20:21,340
[SPEAKER_41]: How are you going to reduce the effect of that?

1128
01:20:23,142 --> 01:20:25,286
[SPEAKER_27]: by bringing the country together.

1129
01:20:25,426 --> 01:20:31,716
[SPEAKER_27]: I think this is such an important point because politics is about the policies that you put forward at the election, obviously.

1130
01:20:32,437 --> 01:20:37,666
[SPEAKER_27]: But it's also about how you do politics and how you deal with difficult topics.

1131
01:20:38,107 --> 01:20:41,893
[SPEAKER_27]: I want to do two things if we get into government in two weeks' time.

1132
01:20:42,042 --> 01:20:44,105
[SPEAKER_27]: and they're about the mindset of government.

1133
01:20:44,406 --> 01:20:52,037
[SPEAKER_27]: The first thing is, I want to return politics to service, because I think it's got far too much into self-entitlement.

1134
01:20:52,057 --> 01:20:53,820
[SPEAKER_27]: Look at the gambling stuff that's going on today.

1135
01:20:54,061 --> 01:20:58,988
[SPEAKER_27]: Politicians who think that making money or self-entitlement is the reason they're in politics.

1136
01:20:59,008 --> 01:21:00,551
[SPEAKER_27]: So we need to return it to service.

1137
01:21:00,571 --> 01:21:07,982
[SPEAKER_27]: The second thing, to go directly to your question, is I want to take the opportunity to bring the country together, because

1138
01:21:07,962 --> 01:21:19,202
[SPEAKER_27]: What's happened in politics, in my view, over the last 10, 15 years or so, is they've become more and more divided and toxic, and everybody's trying to find the difference between us rather than the points of connection.

1139
01:21:19,502 --> 01:21:23,409
[SPEAKER_27]: And Jo Cox, who tragically was murdered, was a good friend of mine.

1140
01:21:23,429 --> 01:21:25,272
[SPEAKER_27]: We came into Parliament at the same time.

1141
01:21:25,353 --> 01:21:27,556
[SPEAKER_27]: Our children are broadly the same age.

1142
01:21:27,576 --> 01:21:31,303
[SPEAKER_27]: What she said in her maiden speech, that we have far more in common,

1143
01:21:31,283 --> 01:21:32,745
[SPEAKER_27]: and we do, which divides us.

1144
01:21:33,105 --> 01:21:34,487
[SPEAKER_27]: That is what I carry.

1145
01:21:34,908 --> 01:21:42,958
[SPEAKER_27]: That is what I want to have the opportunity, if we get into power in two weeks, to implement so that we actually are good at this as a country.

1146
01:21:42,978 --> 01:21:45,922
[SPEAKER_27]: During the pandemic, people were looking out for each other.

1147
01:21:46,263 --> 01:21:51,790
[SPEAKER_27]: Yes, you know, food, medicine, of course, but just the gentle knock on the door of a neighbour that

1148
01:21:51,770 --> 01:21:54,455
[SPEAKER_27]: perhaps we didn't know very well, to say, are you all right?

1149
01:21:54,555 --> 01:21:57,060
[SPEAKER_27]: We're a good country, a reasonable, tolerant country.

1150
01:21:57,341 --> 01:22:01,328
[SPEAKER_27]: We're pretty live and let live if we don't go down the politics of division.

1151
01:22:01,348 --> 01:22:02,571
[SPEAKER_27]: And I want to stop that.

1152
01:22:02,591 --> 01:22:03,533
[SPEAKER_33]: There's lots of questions.

1153
01:22:03,553 --> 01:22:06,819
[SPEAKER_33]: So I'm going to take two or three in a row and then hand over to you.

1154
01:22:07,180 --> 01:22:10,707
[SPEAKER_33]: So the man there in the zip-up top.

1155
01:22:10,727 --> 01:22:11,989
[SPEAKER_33]: Yeah.

1156
01:22:12,982 --> 01:22:22,799
[SPEAKER_13]: You state in your manifesto that you plan on removing the tax breaks for private schools But do you not think that this will put further stress on the already strained state system?

1157
01:22:23,860 --> 01:22:32,475
[SPEAKER_33]: No, I don't Yes, can we can we get a microphone here

1158
01:22:34,700 --> 01:22:45,174
[SPEAKER_44]: There's been a lot of talk about housing policies and helping people to afford their first deposit, but I think one thing that's not taken into consideration is how much money is currently being spent on rent.

1159
01:22:45,194 --> 01:22:46,876
[SPEAKER_44]: So how are we actually meant to save the money?

1160
01:22:46,896 --> 01:22:54,146
[SPEAKER_44]: It's OK building houses, doing 5% deposits, but how am I actually meant to afford to save for that deposit if I'm paying all of that money in rent?

1161
01:22:54,166 --> 01:22:55,728
[SPEAKER_44]: And that's the second part to that.

1162
01:22:56,128 --> 01:23:02,317
[SPEAKER_44]: When will, like, your track record for paying rent count towards you being able to then secure a mortgage?

1163
01:23:02,337 --> 01:23:03,458
[SPEAKER_44]: Because there's lots of people

1164
01:23:03,708 --> 01:23:10,078
[SPEAKER_44]: I, myself, I pay £1,000 in rent each month, but yet I can't afford to get a mortgage, so when will that help?

1165
01:23:10,098 --> 01:23:11,665
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, so that's two pretty meaty questions.

1166
01:23:11,685 --> 01:23:12,790
[SPEAKER_27]: Let's start with private schools.

1167
01:23:13,867 --> 01:23:25,600
[SPEAKER_27]: Look, on private schools, I completely understand that families up and down the country work hard and save hard to send their children to private school because they're aspirational for their children.

1168
01:23:25,620 --> 01:23:29,204
[SPEAKER_27]: But all parents are aspirational for their children, every single parent.

1169
01:23:29,665 --> 01:23:36,893
[SPEAKER_27]: And I want every single child, wherever they come from, whatever their background, and whichever school they go to, to have the same opportunities.

1170
01:23:37,353 --> 01:23:43,620
[SPEAKER_27]: At the moment, in our state secondary schools, we don't have the basic teachers that we need for things like maths.

1171
01:23:44,630 --> 01:23:55,500
[SPEAKER_27]: Now that's really shocking, because if you don't have, some people here and watching will be familiar with maths being taught by the supply teacher, or the PE teacher, but not a designated maths teacher.

1172
01:23:55,520 --> 01:24:10,413
[SPEAKER_27]: That really impacts on the lives of people in our state secondary schools, because if you don't do well at maths, then that inhibits what you can go on to do in A-levels, and it will affect the job you can get, and apprenticeships, et cetera, et cetera.

1173
01:24:10,433 --> 01:24:14,417
[SPEAKER_27]: That's intolerable, so I want to recruit the staff we need

1174
01:24:14,397 --> 01:24:21,669
[SPEAKER_27]: to teach core subjects like maths so that every child, for example, has a maths teacher to teach maths.

1175
01:24:22,110 --> 01:24:26,677
[SPEAKER_27]: In order to fund that, we're going to remove the tax break on private schools.

1176
01:24:26,737 --> 01:24:27,939
[SPEAKER_27]: That's a tough decision.

1177
01:24:27,979 --> 01:24:28,740
[SPEAKER_27]: It's not an easy one.

1178
01:24:28,780 --> 01:24:32,967
[SPEAKER_27]: I do know how hard people work, but I've got to look at it across the board.

1179
01:24:33,248 --> 01:24:36,473
[SPEAKER_27]: I've got to make sure those teachers are there for all children

1180
01:24:36,453 --> 01:24:41,119
[SPEAKER_27]: and make sure that everyone has that chance, so that wherever you come from, whatever your background.

1181
01:24:41,139 --> 01:24:44,884
[SPEAKER_27]: On the question of rent and mortgages, this is a real...

1182
01:24:45,445 --> 01:24:47,067
[SPEAKER_27]: I mean, you're obviously living it.

1183
01:24:47,747 --> 01:25:01,465
[SPEAKER_27]: But, you know, young people who are working hard, you know, on a reasonably decent wage, but then having to pay a huge part of it for rent over and over again, because rents are through the roof, the housing isn't what it should be,

1184
01:25:01,445 --> 01:25:03,551
[SPEAKER_33]: Well there's lots of people who know how bad the problem is.

1185
01:25:03,571 --> 01:25:13,860
[SPEAKER_33]: You're asking very specifically what can be done to help when rents are high and particularly will how much you pay in rent go towards being able to buy a property?

1186
01:25:13,940 --> 01:25:16,467
[SPEAKER_27]: Yeah so on the question of buying property we want

1187
01:25:16,447 --> 01:25:33,460
[SPEAKER_27]: a low deposit scheme, which is what we'll put in place, so that people who've proved they can pay, because they're often paying more for their rent than they pay on their mortgage, so the ability to pay isn't the issue, but they haven't got the ability to save for a mortgage, because mum and dad haven't got the money.

1188
01:25:33,440 --> 01:25:34,942
[SPEAKER_27]: And they're paying it all out on rent.

1189
01:25:35,002 --> 01:25:35,802
[SPEAKER_27]: So that's the first thing.

1190
01:25:35,822 --> 01:25:49,917
[SPEAKER_27]: The second thing, which is also important for those that are in rented accommodation, is we have to stop the landlords ripping off tenants who are doing, you'll probably be familiar, this bidding war, so that when you go to get a rented property, the landlord just does a bidding war.

1191
01:25:49,977 --> 01:25:50,597
[SPEAKER_27]: Who will pay more?

1192
01:25:50,637 --> 01:25:51,218
[SPEAKER_27]: Who will pay more?

1193
01:25:51,238 --> 01:25:51,899
[SPEAKER_27]: Who will pay more?

1194
01:25:52,199 --> 01:25:53,600
[SPEAKER_27]: Until people are paying through the roof.

1195
01:25:53,620 --> 01:25:54,641
[SPEAKER_27]: We have to end that.

1196
01:25:55,002 --> 01:25:56,643
[SPEAKER_33]: How will you end that?

1197
01:25:56,663 --> 01:25:57,584
[SPEAKER_33]: So how will you end that?

1198
01:25:57,604 --> 01:26:00,207
[SPEAKER_33]: If it's private landlords, how can you stop that?

1199
01:26:00,187 --> 01:26:05,394
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, we can pass legislation to say you can't do it, because it is driving rents through the roof, and it's not fair on people.

1200
01:26:05,474 --> 01:26:06,495
[SPEAKER_27]: It's taking advantage of the market.

1201
01:26:06,515 --> 01:26:08,638
[SPEAKER_33]: So what, saying landlords have to, what, take the lowest bidder?

1202
01:26:08,738 --> 01:26:10,059
[SPEAKER_27]: Or, I mean, what's the detail of that?

1203
01:26:10,079 --> 01:26:14,986
[SPEAKER_27]: To put the process around how this is, you cannot have a landlord, or this is what we will outlaw.

1204
01:26:15,006 --> 01:26:22,976
[SPEAKER_33]: I appreciate what you're saying cannot happen, but I'm just wondering specifically, if you've got a private landlord saying, I want to give it to this person or that person, how do you legislate for that not to happen?

1205
01:26:22,996 --> 01:26:24,457
[SPEAKER_27]: No, that's not how they do it.

1206
01:26:24,598 --> 01:26:25,899
[SPEAKER_27]: That's not how they do it.

1207
01:26:25,919 --> 01:26:28,182
[SPEAKER_27]: They say, one person says x pounds a week.

1208
01:26:28,202 --> 01:26:29,704
[SPEAKER_27]: Someone says, I'll give you x plus.

1209
01:26:29,920 --> 01:26:31,043
[SPEAKER_27]: £10, £20, £30.

1210
01:26:31,303 --> 01:26:36,315
[SPEAKER_27]: They then go back to the first person and say, I've already had a better offer for X plus this.

1211
01:26:36,796 --> 01:26:39,703
[SPEAKER_27]: So you get this bidding war going on until the rents go through the roof.

1212
01:26:39,723 --> 01:26:41,126
[SPEAKER_27]: So you're saying they have to take the first offer.

1213
01:26:41,146 --> 01:26:42,590
[SPEAKER_27]: Is that what you're saying for private landlords?

1214
01:26:42,610 --> 01:26:44,514
[SPEAKER_27]: No, we can't have this bidding war like this.

1215
01:26:44,574 --> 01:26:45,396
[SPEAKER_33]: No, I get that.

1216
01:26:45,476 --> 01:26:47,541
[SPEAKER_33]: Are you telling private landlords they have to take the first offer then?

1217
01:26:47,521 --> 01:26:51,407
[SPEAKER_27]: They have to... We have to have a scheme in place to stop them driving the rent up and up and up.

1218
01:26:51,427 --> 01:26:53,229
[SPEAKER_27]: OK, I'm still not entirely clear how you're going to do that.

1219
01:26:53,249 --> 01:27:04,525
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, no, no, but the other thing I do want to address is this, which is deposits... Lots of renters are paying huge deposits, and we have to stop that as well and make sure the conditions are good within the housing they're buying.

1220
01:27:04,545 --> 01:27:12,837
[SPEAKER_27]: But at the end of the day, there's no way out of the renting problem until we build more houses, because without the houses that people can afford to live in and buy,

1221
01:27:12,817 --> 01:27:18,747
[SPEAKER_27]: then more people are renting, and that is bingo for landlords who are making a fortune out of this.

1222
01:27:19,227 --> 01:27:21,952
[SPEAKER_33]: OK. Our time is up, Keir Starmer.

1223
01:27:22,132 --> 01:27:24,276
[SPEAKER_33]: Thank you very much for all your questions, Keir Starmer.

1224
01:27:24,296 --> 01:27:25,978
[SPEAKER_33]: Thank you for your time with us here this evening.

1225
01:27:25,998 --> 01:27:34,192
[SPEAKER_33]: Thank you.

1226
01:27:34,212 --> 01:27:34,993
[SPEAKER_33]: APPLAUSE Right.

1227
01:27:36,593 --> 01:27:37,974
[SPEAKER_33]: Are you still with me at home?

1228
01:27:38,375 --> 01:27:39,436
[SPEAKER_33]: We're in the home straight.

1229
01:27:39,456 --> 01:27:40,858
[SPEAKER_33]: We've got the last half hour now.

1230
01:27:40,878 --> 01:27:47,605
[SPEAKER_33]: So, would you please welcome our final guest tonight, the Conservative leader, and, of course, our Prime Minister, Rishi Sunak.

1231
01:28:00,419 --> 01:28:01,420
[SPEAKER_23]: APPLAUSE Hi.

1232
01:28:01,440 --> 01:28:01,760
[SPEAKER_33]: Nice to see you.

1233
01:28:01,780 --> 01:28:01,840
[SPEAKER_33]: OK.

1234
01:28:01,860 --> 01:28:02,681
[SPEAKER_33]: So, we've got a number of questions.

1235
01:28:02,701 --> 01:28:03,382
[SPEAKER_33]: We've got about half an hour.

1236
01:28:03,402 --> 01:28:04,203
[SPEAKER_33]: I'm going to try and get through them.

1237
01:28:04,223 --> 01:28:06,145
[SPEAKER_33]: Let's start with our first one, which is from Kevin Dobson.

1238
01:28:07,424 --> 01:28:14,937
[SPEAKER_18]: Hi, we've had five Prime Ministers in the last seven years and one of them managed to last for six weeks.

1239
01:28:15,858 --> 01:28:20,286
[SPEAKER_18]: As a result, I think we are something of an international laughingstock.

1240
01:28:20,847 --> 01:28:29,061
[SPEAKER_18]: I'm asking if you would confess to us tonight even just a small amount of embarrassment to be leading the Conservative Party into this election campaign.

1241
01:28:35,183 --> 01:28:36,265
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, good evening, everyone.

1242
01:28:36,345 --> 01:28:37,768
[SPEAKER_20]: Fiona, thank you for inviting me.

1243
01:28:37,848 --> 01:28:38,970
[SPEAKER_20]: And Kevin, was that right?

1244
01:28:39,612 --> 01:28:39,712
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah.

1245
01:28:39,732 --> 01:28:46,845
[SPEAKER_20]: When I first got this job, I stood on the steps of Downing Street and spoke to all of you as Prime Minister for the first time, and I acknowledged that.

1246
01:28:47,807 --> 01:28:52,617
[SPEAKER_20]: I said very clearly that mistakes had been made, and that's why I was standing there in front of you.

1247
01:28:52,937 --> 01:28:55,943
[SPEAKER_20]: In fact, you may remember I spent the summer before that

1248
01:28:56,412 --> 01:28:59,876
[SPEAKER_20]: arguing against the policies that my predecessor had suggested were right.

1249
01:28:59,996 --> 01:29:02,258
[SPEAKER_20]: I didn't think they were right for the country, and I said so.

1250
01:29:02,959 --> 01:29:06,483
[SPEAKER_20]: But what I'd ask you to do is judge me on my 18 months that I've been in office.

1251
01:29:07,024 --> 01:29:12,970
[SPEAKER_20]: I came in with one primary job, and that was to bring back economic stability after the difficult few years that we've had.

1252
01:29:13,411 --> 01:29:17,576
[SPEAKER_20]: You saw yesterday, we had the very welcome news that inflation is back to target.

1253
01:29:17,856 --> 01:29:24,343
[SPEAKER_20]: Now, I know that that's only starting to make a difference to all of your lives and everyone else's, but that's the path we're on.

1254
01:29:24,323 --> 01:29:32,515
[SPEAKER_20]: And if we stick with that path, I can continue to cut your taxes, give you more financial security, and actually deliver on the things that I know you want me to.

1255
01:29:33,577 --> 01:29:38,224
[SPEAKER_33]: So Kevin's question is about character, it's about trust, it's about integrity.

1256
01:29:38,364 --> 01:29:39,185
[SPEAKER_33]: I think it's fair to say.

1257
01:29:39,566 --> 01:29:43,832
[SPEAKER_33]: We've got a question from Graham Donald on matters more recent.

1258
01:29:44,053 --> 01:29:45,555
[SPEAKER_33]: Graham.

1259
01:29:46,008 --> 01:29:59,190
[SPEAKER_19]: Aren't these emerging allegations about betting on the election date the absolute epitome of the lack of ethics that we have had to tolerate from the Conservative Party for years and years?

1260
01:30:05,768 --> 01:30:13,574
[SPEAKER_33]: Just to be clear, for those of you who might not have kept up with it, three people are being investigated by the Gambling Commission about placing a bet on the timing of the election.

1261
01:30:14,056 --> 01:30:16,825
[SPEAKER_33]: Two are Conservative Party candidates.

1262
01:30:17,395 --> 01:30:25,251
[SPEAKER_33]: Craig Williams, Laura Saunders, and her husband, Tony Lee, is the Conservative Party Director of Campaigning.

1263
01:30:25,932 --> 01:30:26,854
[SPEAKER_33]: They are being investigated.

1264
01:30:26,874 --> 01:30:29,760
[SPEAKER_33]: There's also an issue with a police officer who has been arrested.

1265
01:30:30,060 --> 01:30:32,365
[SPEAKER_33]: But these are three people connected to the Conservative Party.

1266
01:30:32,666 --> 01:30:35,231
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, like you, I was incredibly angry.

1267
01:30:36,052 --> 01:30:39,319
[SPEAKER_20]: Incredibly angry to learn of these allegations.

1268
01:30:39,822 --> 01:30:41,525
[SPEAKER_20]: It's a really serious matter.

1269
01:30:41,865 --> 01:30:51,121
[SPEAKER_20]: It's right that they're being investigated properly by the relevant law enforcement authorities, including, as Fiona said, a criminal investigation by the police.

1270
01:30:52,163 --> 01:30:58,513
[SPEAKER_20]: I want to be crystal clear that if anyone has broken the rules, they should face the full force of the law.

1271
01:30:58,814 --> 01:31:00,737
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's what those investigations are there to do.

1272
01:31:01,077 --> 01:31:03,822
[SPEAKER_20]: And I hope that they do their work as quickly and as thoroughly as possible.

1273
01:31:03,970 --> 01:31:05,471
[SPEAKER_33]: There are calls for them to be suspended.

1274
01:31:05,631 --> 01:31:07,573
[SPEAKER_33]: These are party candidates.

1275
01:31:08,514 --> 01:31:11,997
[SPEAKER_33]: But you're happy not to suspend them, to let them carry on and go on to the election.

1276
01:31:12,017 --> 01:31:13,979
[SPEAKER_33]: Obviously, they've not admitted anything.

1277
01:31:13,999 --> 01:31:17,122
[SPEAKER_33]: No one is saying that a decision has been taken about their guilt or their innocence.

1278
01:31:17,642 --> 01:31:21,766
[SPEAKER_33]: But you're happy for them to go into the election and represent you and the Conservative Party.

1279
01:31:21,786 --> 01:31:24,188
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, Fiona, as you said, these investigations are ongoing.

1280
01:31:24,869 --> 01:31:26,771
[SPEAKER_20]: They are rightly confidential.

1281
01:31:27,231 --> 01:31:30,454
[SPEAKER_20]: One of them is a criminal investigation that's been conducted by the police.

1282
01:31:30,794 --> 01:31:31,655
[SPEAKER_20]: These are very serious matters.

1283
01:31:31,675 --> 01:31:32,396
[SPEAKER_33]: Yes, but that's a police officer.

1284
01:31:32,556 --> 01:31:33,977
[SPEAKER_33]: Talk about the two party candidates.

1285
01:31:33,957 --> 01:31:52,070
[SPEAKER_20]: All I can say is, they are serious investigations, it's right that they are done thoroughly, confidentially, the integrity of that process should be respected, but what I can tell you is if anyone is found to have broken the rules, not only should they face the full consequences of the law, I will make sure that they are booted out of the Conservative Party.

1286
01:31:53,413 --> 01:31:56,218
[SPEAKER_33]: Woman there in the white T-shirt.

1287
01:31:56,536 --> 01:32:09,925
[SPEAKER_45]: As a parent of 17-year-olds who have grown up in the last five years against the backdrop of COVID and the shenanigans of the Tory party, what are you going to do as a political party to rebuild trust in young people and politicians?

1288
01:32:11,989 --> 01:32:13,212
[SPEAKER_33]: There's a bit of a theme emerging.

1289
01:32:15,976 --> 01:32:20,874
[SPEAKER_20]: You know, if you're asking about why you can trust me in particular, I'll tell you.

1290
01:32:21,496 --> 01:32:27,117
[SPEAKER_20]: Actually, very simply, it's because my grandparents came to this country with very little.

1291
01:32:27,535 --> 01:32:30,778
[SPEAKER_20]: And in two generations, I'm standing here as your Prime Minister.

1292
01:32:31,278 --> 01:32:34,501
[SPEAKER_20]: So this country did something extraordinary for my family.

1293
01:32:35,082 --> 01:32:38,205
[SPEAKER_20]: And I feel an enormous debt of gratitude to repay that.

1294
01:32:38,645 --> 01:32:45,771
[SPEAKER_20]: And I'm in this so that I can make the same difference to as many people as possible as the difference that this country made to my family.

1295
01:32:46,172 --> 01:32:55,560
[SPEAKER_20]: So I can happily talk to you about lots of policies like national service, helping your children get onto the housing ladder with cuts to stamp duty, getting them great apprenticeships.

1296
01:32:55,760 --> 01:32:57,542
[SPEAKER_20]: But fundamentally, I'm in this

1297
01:32:57,522 --> 01:33:06,813
[SPEAKER_20]: because of what this country has done for my family, and I will work very hard to repay that and make as many people's lives better in the way that my life has been transformed by being here.

1298
01:33:06,833 --> 01:33:11,258
[SPEAKER_45]: National Service is not something that young people that I speak to are particularly interested in.

1299
01:33:11,278 --> 01:33:13,480
[SPEAKER_45]: They do a lot of volunteering and other things already on their own.

1300
01:33:14,081 --> 01:33:24,593
[SPEAKER_45]: It was more about the trust that young people can get from all politicians in the last five years, growing up against that, and the trust that can be rebuilt in politicians in general.

1301
01:33:24,995 --> 01:33:26,438
[SPEAKER_33]: OK, I think you've answered that.

1302
01:33:26,458 --> 01:33:27,400
[SPEAKER_33]: Let's take another question now.

1303
01:33:27,760 --> 01:33:30,866
[SPEAKER_33]: This man in the blue sweater and blue shirt.

1304
01:33:30,886 --> 01:33:30,986
[SPEAKER_33]: Yeah.

1305
01:33:32,669 --> 01:33:39,663
[SPEAKER_05]: Despite my personal support for the scheme, many of my peers at school, so I'm a college student, many of my peers can't see the potential benefits from the National Service Scheme.

1306
01:33:40,144 --> 01:33:43,590
[SPEAKER_05]: How are you going to enforce and also insensitise young people to take up the scheme?

1307
01:33:43,951 --> 01:33:44,732
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah.

1308
01:33:44,752 --> 01:33:48,319
[SPEAKER_20]: So, actually, I've been everywhere across the country talking to young people about it.

1309
01:33:48,299 --> 01:33:52,226
[SPEAKER_20]: and talking to parents about it, and I've heard an enormous amount of support for it.

1310
01:33:52,286 --> 01:33:52,847
[SPEAKER_20]: And I'll tell you why.

1311
01:33:53,228 --> 01:34:03,566
[SPEAKER_20]: I was with someone just the other day who I'd seen in the evening, someone in their early 20s, probably not that dissimilar in age from you, and they were telling me about something that had just happened to them that afternoon.

1312
01:34:04,367 --> 01:34:07,793
[SPEAKER_20]: They had seen an elderly person fall and...

1313
01:34:07,773 --> 01:34:19,388
[SPEAKER_20]: damaged their hip quite badly, and because they had volunteered with St John's Ambulance, they were able to help that person and be with them, give them some sense of reassurance, get the ambulance there, and that person was incredibly grateful.

1314
01:34:19,648 --> 01:34:36,430
[SPEAKER_20]: And then I was talking to this person a little bit more, and they were explaining how they'd got into St John's Ambulance because they'd been through a difficult time in their lives, and it was something that they did to give them a sense of purpose and contribution to society, and they found it a really fulfilling and meaningful experience, as well as, in that case, giving them some skills, practical skills,

1315
01:34:36,410 --> 01:34:39,114
[SPEAKER_20]: that have allowed them to help other people in their life.

1316
01:34:39,295 --> 01:34:41,859
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's why I think national service is a good idea.

1317
01:34:42,139 --> 01:34:52,716
[SPEAKER_20]: That one person's example is a great reason to spread this to as many people as possible, make sure everyone can have those skills and opportunities, have a sense of contributing to something bigger than themselves.

1318
01:34:52,796 --> 01:34:58,705
[SPEAKER_20]: I think that gives people meaning and purpose, and also contribute to our country's overall resilience and security.

1319
01:34:59,186 --> 01:35:03,733
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's why, as I said, that one story encapsulates, I think, very well why this is a great idea.

1320
01:35:03,713 --> 01:35:05,035
[SPEAKER_33]: So you say you've been talking to young people.

1321
01:35:05,055 --> 01:35:05,776
[SPEAKER_33]: You've got us at one straight.

1322
01:35:05,797 --> 01:35:08,782
[SPEAKER_33]: Have you also been talking to your former chief of the naval staff, who says he's bonkers?

1323
01:35:10,084 --> 01:35:12,929
[SPEAKER_33]: And the former chief of the general staff, who says it's electoral opportunism.

1324
01:35:12,949 --> 01:35:13,650
[SPEAKER_33]: Have you spoken to them?

1325
01:35:13,810 --> 01:35:15,573
[SPEAKER_20]: I've spoken to lots of people in the armed forces.

1326
01:35:15,593 --> 01:35:16,374
[SPEAKER_20]: Have you spoken to them?

1327
01:35:16,394 --> 01:35:20,802
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, I wouldn't be appropriate, Fiona, to start politicising the armed forces in an election campaign.

1328
01:35:20,862 --> 01:35:26,852
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, it's just they've been very critical of your campaign, and given they know a bit or two about the army, I wonder if you thought you might find out why they're so critical.

1329
01:35:26,832 --> 01:35:34,859
[SPEAKER_20]: Because I've spoken to lots of people in the armed forces, and they themselves have been working on schemes to make it easier for young people to engage with the armed forces.

1330
01:35:35,079 --> 01:35:37,001
[SPEAKER_20]: That's something that they themselves have been working on.

1331
01:35:37,301 --> 01:35:39,763
[SPEAKER_20]: Those are the conversations I've been having with them for many months.

1332
01:35:39,883 --> 01:35:45,027
[SPEAKER_20]: And it's really important for people to know the military option is optional.

1333
01:35:45,047 --> 01:35:45,187
[SPEAKER_20]: Right?

1334
01:35:45,207 --> 01:35:46,468
[SPEAKER_20]: No-one's going to be forced to do it.

1335
01:35:46,509 --> 01:35:47,770
[SPEAKER_20]: It's actually going to be very selective, competitive.

1336
01:35:47,810 --> 01:35:50,312
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, the whole thing's going to be optional, isn't it?

1337
01:35:50,332 --> 01:35:51,793
[SPEAKER_20]: National service will be compulsory.

1338
01:35:51,813 --> 01:35:54,996
[SPEAKER_20]: The military option will be something that people choose to do.

1339
01:35:55,016 --> 01:35:55,216
[SPEAKER_33]: Oh, I see.

1340
01:35:55,236 --> 01:35:56,637
[SPEAKER_33]: So how will you make people do it?

1341
01:35:57,528 --> 01:35:57,809
[SPEAKER_20]: Sorry?

1342
01:35:57,989 --> 01:36:00,676
[SPEAKER_33]: If national service is going to be compulsory, how will you make people do it?

1343
01:36:01,097 --> 01:36:07,071
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, you'll have a set of sanctions and incentives, and we will look at the models that are existing around Europe to get the appropriate mix of those.

1344
01:36:07,231 --> 01:36:09,216
[SPEAKER_20]: There's a range of different options that exist.

1345
01:36:09,236 --> 01:36:09,597
[SPEAKER_42]: For example?

1346
01:36:09,880 --> 01:36:16,670
[SPEAKER_20]: There's all sorts of things that people do across Europe, whether that's looking at driving licenses, other access to finance, all sorts of other things.

1347
01:36:16,750 --> 01:36:18,493
[SPEAKER_20]: The right thing to do is to allow... Access to finance?

1348
01:36:19,014 --> 01:36:19,094
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes.

1349
01:36:19,114 --> 01:36:23,541
[SPEAKER_33]: So if people don't want to do national service, what, you're going to take their bank cards away?

1350
01:36:23,581 --> 01:36:24,763
[SPEAKER_20]: No, no, there's access.

1351
01:36:25,824 --> 01:36:28,308
[SPEAKER_20]: There's lots of different models around Europe.

1352
01:36:28,568 --> 01:36:29,950
[SPEAKER_20]: There's lots of different models around Europe.

1353
01:36:29,971 --> 01:36:31,613
[SPEAKER_20]: This is being done in multiple countries in Europe.

1354
01:36:31,633 --> 01:36:31,974
[SPEAKER_33]: I don't doubt it.

1355
01:36:31,994 --> 01:36:32,935
[SPEAKER_33]: I'm just asking what you think.

1356
01:36:32,915 --> 01:36:40,856
[SPEAKER_20]: So there's a range of things, and we will have a royal commission look at all of those, come back to the government, and recommend what the appropriate mix of incentives and sanctions is.

1357
01:36:41,378 --> 01:36:42,300
[SPEAKER_33]: OK. Matt here in the blue shirt.

1358
01:36:44,407 --> 01:36:55,202
[SPEAKER_25]: Four and a half years ago, the Conservative Party campaigned on the oven-ready deal so that Brexit would be done and it would be great for the country, and that was the heart of your election promises.

1359
01:36:55,762 --> 01:37:01,390
[SPEAKER_25]: Why now, four and a half years later, aren't you saying, look how great Brexit's been for us?

1360
01:37:01,670 --> 01:37:05,976
[SPEAKER_25]: It's something that's absent from your manifesto.

1361
01:37:05,956 --> 01:37:13,687
[SPEAKER_25]: What's happened with Brexit has been particularly affecting to young people, their ability to work and educate abroad.

1362
01:37:14,267 --> 01:37:17,171
[SPEAKER_25]: And we've benefited from Europe.

1363
01:37:17,232 --> 01:37:20,176
[SPEAKER_25]: We've benefited from low house prices, from good pensions.

1364
01:37:20,576 --> 01:37:22,979
[SPEAKER_25]: We're throwing young people into the fire.

1365
01:37:22,999 --> 01:37:25,483
[SPEAKER_25]: And I just don't see anything that you're doing for them.

1366
01:37:27,426 --> 01:37:28,487
So just to be clear, it's your question about Brexit.

1367
01:37:29,260 --> 01:37:33,334
[SPEAKER_25]: You're questioning about Brexit or about young people?

1368
01:37:33,354 --> 01:37:38,633
[SPEAKER_25]: It's about how Brexit has denied young people a future.

1369
01:37:39,657 --> 01:37:40,941
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, look.

1370
01:37:42,794 --> 01:37:58,280
[SPEAKER_20]: We had all these debates several years ago, I'm not going to re-litigate them, we had a referendum and the country decided and now the job is to get on and make sure we realise all the benefits of that and actually don't have to go very far from here to see it in a very tangible way for young people.

1371
01:37:58,961 --> 01:38:01,225
[SPEAKER_20]: In Teesside there's something called a free poll.

1372
01:38:01,205 --> 01:38:06,193
[SPEAKER_20]: which is a special investment zone that we created using our freedoms from Brexit.

1373
01:38:06,213 --> 01:38:10,661
[SPEAKER_20]: It's attracting billions of pounds of investment, creating thousands of incredibly high-quality jobs.

1374
01:38:10,681 --> 01:38:21,459
[SPEAKER_20]: I was there recently talking to young apprentices who are now doing fantastic careers in the growth industries of the future, incredibly excited about what that is for them and what that means.

1375
01:38:21,559 --> 01:38:23,001
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's just one of the examples of things that we're doing.

1376
01:38:23,022 --> 01:38:25,325
[SPEAKER_33]: You couldn't have open free ports without leaving the EU, Prime Minister, as you know.

1377
01:38:25,345 --> 01:38:26,908
[SPEAKER_20]: No, you can't have in the same way, Fiona.

1378
01:38:26,888 --> 01:38:27,869
[SPEAKER_33]: in the same way.

1379
01:38:27,890 --> 01:38:37,845
[SPEAKER_20]: It is exactly how we have done them that means we are attracting the investment and creating the jobs, which is already making a difference to so many people's lives.

1380
01:38:38,165 --> 01:38:40,308
[SPEAKER_20]: That is a practical example of what we have done.

1381
01:38:40,328 --> 01:38:42,792
[SPEAKER_20]: The choice at this election is about the future.

1382
01:38:43,112 --> 01:38:45,115
[SPEAKER_20]: We are not going to go back to Brexit.

1383
01:38:45,176 --> 01:38:46,337
[SPEAKER_20]: This is about the future.

1384
01:38:46,498 --> 01:38:48,120
[SPEAKER_20]: When it comes to the economy,

1385
01:38:48,100 --> 01:39:05,265
[SPEAKER_20]: And when it comes to making sure people who are working hard have the opportunities they deserve, what I want to do is build on the progress we've made and give you and every other young person that you're concerned about the opportunity to get a job with a new apprentice, if that's the right thing for them, and then keep more of their hard-earned money by cutting their taxes.

1386
01:39:05,425 --> 01:39:06,828
[SPEAKER_20]: That is what I want to do for people.

1387
01:39:07,068 --> 01:39:13,577
[SPEAKER_20]: And actually, outside of the EU, we're able to do things that will drive more growth, create more jobs that will allow me to cut more taxes.

1388
01:39:13,878 --> 01:39:15,340
[SPEAKER_20]: That's the choice at this election.

1389
01:39:15,640 --> 01:39:17,604
[SPEAKER_33]: Can we take a question from Ronald Thorne?

1390
01:39:18,627 --> 01:39:20,130
[SPEAKER_33]: There you are.

1391
01:39:20,150 --> 01:39:24,600
[SPEAKER_08]: Mr Sunak, recent figures show NHS waiting lists have more than doubled under your government.

1392
01:39:25,482 --> 01:39:31,135
[SPEAKER_08]: What message have you got for those who are on waiting lists, particularly those who have been on there for more than one year?

1393
01:39:31,520 --> 01:39:33,664
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, Ronald, first thing, it was Ronald, wasn't it?

1394
01:39:34,185 --> 01:39:34,766
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah.

1395
01:39:34,787 --> 01:39:42,562
[SPEAKER_20]: I come from an NHS family, so I was raised with people, surrounded by people who dedicated their lives to trying to make their patients' lives a bit easier.

1396
01:39:43,203 --> 01:39:45,909
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's what I spent my childhood doing and working in.

1397
01:39:45,929 --> 01:39:47,752
[SPEAKER_20]: So the NHS matters to me personally.

1398
01:39:48,374 --> 01:39:53,123
[SPEAKER_20]: And we haven't made as much progress as I would have liked, tackling waiting lists in the last...

1399
01:39:53,103 --> 01:39:53,824
[SPEAKER_20]: 18 months.

1400
01:39:53,924 --> 01:39:55,165
[SPEAKER_33]: And you haven't kept your pledge either?

1401
01:39:55,265 --> 01:40:00,631
[SPEAKER_20]: We have not made as much progress as we would have liked, as I would have liked.

1402
01:40:01,292 --> 01:40:04,916
[SPEAKER_20]: But what I can tell you is we are putting record investment into the NHS.

1403
01:40:05,176 --> 01:40:15,668
[SPEAKER_20]: We've got more doctors and nurses working in it than we ever have and we're training more and we're doing different things, making sure that we can diagnose people's cancers earlier by doing scans closer to their homes.

1404
01:40:15,648 --> 01:40:19,197
[SPEAKER_20]: allowing you to do more things at your pharmacy to get the treatment that you need quicker.

1405
01:40:19,418 --> 01:40:21,724
[SPEAKER_20]: And those things are starting to make a difference.

1406
01:40:21,744 --> 01:40:26,136
[SPEAKER_20]: And what we've seen over the past few months is waiting lists now are starting to come down.

1407
01:40:26,236 --> 01:40:27,058
[SPEAKER_20]: They've just gone up.

1408
01:40:27,713 --> 01:40:31,941
[SPEAKER_20]: over the past few months, over the past five months, they've gone down by around 200,000.

1409
01:40:31,961 --> 01:40:35,327
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, they're still higher than where you were, and they have literally just gone up.

1410
01:40:35,347 --> 01:40:36,329
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm sure you have.

1411
01:40:36,349 --> 01:40:37,791
[SPEAKER_20]: Fiona, I freely acknowledge that.

1412
01:40:38,012 --> 01:40:39,134
[SPEAKER_33]: OK, I just want to be clear.

1413
01:40:39,154 --> 01:40:39,695
[SPEAKER_20]: I freely acknowledge that.

1414
01:40:39,715 --> 01:40:41,498
[SPEAKER_20]: But, Fiona, this is an important point, right?

1415
01:40:41,618 --> 01:40:43,702
[SPEAKER_20]: Inflation yesterday hit 2%.

1416
01:40:43,982 --> 01:40:46,026
[SPEAKER_20]: When I became Prime Minister, it was 11%.

1417
01:40:46,242 --> 01:40:49,607
[SPEAKER_20]: Now, that is something that I said I would do, and we've done it.

1418
01:40:49,647 --> 01:40:51,429
[SPEAKER_20]: Now, these things don't happen overnight.

1419
01:40:51,530 --> 01:40:52,932
[SPEAKER_20]: They don't happen in a straight line.

1420
01:40:53,332 --> 01:40:56,316
[SPEAKER_20]: But if you have a plan and you stick to it, you can get the results.

1421
01:40:56,336 --> 01:40:57,638
[SPEAKER_20]: You've seen that on inflation.

1422
01:40:57,879 --> 01:40:59,060
[SPEAKER_20]: You've seen me stick to a plan.

1423
01:40:59,201 --> 01:41:03,266
[SPEAKER_20]: And yes, during that period, it popped up a couple of times, and everyone said the same.

1424
01:41:03,306 --> 01:41:04,809
[SPEAKER_20]: And I said, if we stick to it, we will get it there.

1425
01:41:04,889 --> 01:41:05,229
[SPEAKER_20]: We did.

1426
01:41:05,510 --> 01:41:08,153
[SPEAKER_20]: And on waiting lists, we haven't made as much progress as I would have liked.

1427
01:41:08,394 --> 01:41:10,697
[SPEAKER_20]: But because of the things we are doing,

1428
01:41:10,677 --> 01:41:14,203
[SPEAKER_20]: What you have seen over this year is waiting lists are now starting to come down.

1429
01:41:14,383 --> 01:41:18,510
[SPEAKER_20]: There is still a way to go, of course there is, but we will stick to it and I will get it done.

1430
01:41:19,492 --> 01:41:19,892
[SPEAKER_33]: Convinced?

1431
01:41:20,974 --> 01:41:21,174
[SPEAKER_08]: No.

1432
01:41:21,215 --> 01:41:26,323
[SPEAKER_08]: So your message to the people who are still on the waiting list is, sorry, but we could do better.

1433
01:41:27,620 --> 01:41:39,720
[SPEAKER_20]: What I want to do is make sure they get their treatment as quickly as possible, which is why we're putting more money in, hiring more doctors and nurses, and doing things differently so they can get the care they need in different ways, often outside of hospitals.

1434
01:41:39,980 --> 01:41:42,504
[SPEAKER_20]: Now, I can't promise that's going to be solved overnight.

1435
01:41:42,524 --> 01:41:45,429
[SPEAKER_20]: And to give you the context here, Ronald, here's the thing that we're grappling with.

1436
01:41:46,090 --> 01:41:51,519
[SPEAKER_20]: During the pandemic, six million referrals that otherwise would have happened didn't happen.

1437
01:41:51,899 --> 01:41:53,141
[SPEAKER_20]: Just think about that for a second.

1438
01:41:53,302 --> 01:41:54,724
[SPEAKER_20]: Six million.

1439
01:41:55,345 --> 01:41:57,288
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's what we're now grappling with.

1440
01:41:58,149 --> 01:42:00,874
[SPEAKER_20]: That's why the NHS is under the pressure that it's under.

1441
01:42:01,034 --> 01:42:04,399
[SPEAKER_20]: Six million missed referrals that we are now catching up on.

1442
01:42:05,160 --> 01:42:11,430
[SPEAKER_20]: So the NHS is doing more today than it's ever done in its history because of the investment we've done and all the improvements we've made.

1443
01:42:11,450 --> 01:42:12,612
[SPEAKER_20]: It's not treating more people.

1444
01:42:12,592 --> 01:42:19,487
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes, the NHS is today carrying out more checks, tests, scans, operations, treatments, appointments than it's done in its history.

1445
01:42:19,748 --> 01:42:26,744
[SPEAKER_20]: But when you're dealing with a six million missed referrals that we are now catching up on, it is going to take time to get them down.

1446
01:42:27,065 --> 01:42:28,187
[SPEAKER_33]: Let's have this man here in the front.

1447
01:42:31,238 --> 01:42:35,464
[SPEAKER_12]: So I'm glad, Rishi, you said that there is family who has NHS.

1448
01:42:35,925 --> 01:42:39,390
[SPEAKER_12]: You say that there is more operations and patients are more.

1449
01:42:39,811 --> 01:42:41,152
[SPEAKER_12]: I am frontline person.

1450
01:42:41,213 --> 01:42:42,234
[SPEAKER_12]: I work in NHS.

1451
01:42:42,494 --> 01:42:43,416
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm a doctor here.

1452
01:42:43,836 --> 01:42:49,705
[SPEAKER_12]: And I am more frustrated now than I was before because every time there is no funding, nothing.

1453
01:42:50,086 --> 01:42:57,136
[SPEAKER_12]: Even for children who are having constipation, soiling, they are being called smelly boy, smelly girl in the school.

1454
01:42:57,436 --> 01:42:59,980
[SPEAKER_12]: They are saying nurses will not provide the service.

1455
01:42:59,960 --> 01:43:05,509
[SPEAKER_12]: How can you say that the parents will be confident who are frustrated now?

1456
01:43:05,770 --> 01:43:08,895
[SPEAKER_12]: The NHS staff, the staff moral is all the way down.

1457
01:43:09,196 --> 01:43:12,101
[SPEAKER_12]: There are more strikes in your period than ever before.

1458
01:43:12,141 --> 01:43:16,148
[SPEAKER_12]: What would you say to that, that people are suffering?

1459
01:43:16,468 --> 01:43:24,702
[SPEAKER_12]: The doctors are, the nurses, the therapists, everywhere, the patients are suffering, waiting lists are going up.

1460
01:43:24,682 --> 01:43:25,984
[SPEAKER_12]: You said it is going down.

1461
01:43:26,425 --> 01:43:27,948
[SPEAKER_12]: I don't know what you said.

1462
01:43:28,288 --> 01:43:31,534
[SPEAKER_12]: And then you said 10 billion more investment in your manifesto.

1463
01:43:32,015 --> 01:43:33,017
[SPEAKER_12]: What is going to happen?

1464
01:43:33,397 --> 01:43:34,279
[SPEAKER_12]: How do we trust?

1465
01:43:34,800 --> 01:43:35,681
[SPEAKER_12]: Is it going to happen?

1466
01:43:35,962 --> 01:43:44,597
[SPEAKER_12]: And this is, I think, in my view, an eyewash rather than a true deliverable goal.

1467
01:43:50,855 --> 01:43:55,165
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, there is more money going into the NHS today than there has been in its history.

1468
01:43:55,225 --> 01:43:59,234
[SPEAKER_20]: And I'm sure BBC Verify after that, this debate, will verify that for you.

1469
01:43:59,715 --> 01:44:00,416
[SPEAKER_20]: But that is the fact.

1470
01:44:00,517 --> 01:44:02,040
[SPEAKER_20]: But I don't dismiss your concerns.

1471
01:44:02,060 --> 01:44:04,225
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, inflation might have something to do with that, but yes.

1472
01:44:05,047 --> 01:44:06,570
[SPEAKER_20]: I absolutely acknowledge your concerns.

1473
01:44:06,590 --> 01:44:08,695
[SPEAKER_20]: You and your colleagues are working very hard.

1474
01:44:08,675 --> 01:44:17,947
[SPEAKER_20]: You were doing more than we've ever done before, but the situation is challenging because we are dealing with the backlog of missed appointments that you are very well aware of, and I'm sure you were working hard during COVID.

1475
01:44:18,187 --> 01:44:22,473
[SPEAKER_20]: You saw what didn't happen during that period, but you talked about parents and children.

1476
01:44:22,493 --> 01:44:26,739
[SPEAKER_20]: I'll give you one practical example of something that we're doing that is already making a difference.

1477
01:44:27,079 --> 01:44:27,780
[SPEAKER_20]: Now,

1478
01:44:28,250 --> 01:44:40,702
[SPEAKER_20]: Because of the changes that we've made, if your child has an ear infection, a sore throat, sinusitis, instead of having to make a GP appointment, you can now go direct to your pharmacist to get the medicines that you need.

1479
01:44:41,103 --> 01:44:44,672
[SPEAKER_20]: That change that we have made is making an enormous difference already.

1480
01:44:44,652 --> 01:44:50,200
[SPEAKER_20]: saving parents an enormous amount of time, making sure their children get the care and the medicines they need much quicker.

1481
01:44:50,500 --> 01:44:55,146
[SPEAKER_20]: And if I'm re-elected, we will expand that Pharmacy First programme to cover more different illnesses.

1482
01:44:55,407 --> 01:44:57,309
[SPEAKER_20]: And again, these things all add up.

1483
01:44:57,429 --> 01:45:07,243
[SPEAKER_20]: No one thing is going to solve the problem, but it's just a demonstration to you of my commitment to making sure you and everyone else has an NHS that they can rely on, having the peace of mind that it's there for them when they need.

1484
01:45:07,763 --> 01:45:08,905
[SPEAKER_33]: A bit less frustrated now?

1485
01:45:09,475 --> 01:45:10,436
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm not sure.

1486
01:45:11,938 --> 01:45:12,838
[SPEAKER_33]: All right, you're not sure.

1487
01:45:12,899 --> 01:45:14,120
[SPEAKER_33]: OK, let's take another question.

1488
01:45:14,140 --> 01:45:14,620
[SPEAKER_33]: Woman there.

1489
01:45:14,640 --> 01:45:16,682
[SPEAKER_43]: Yeah.

1490
01:45:16,702 --> 01:45:24,871
[SPEAKER_43]: Employed migrant workers such as myself or your parents, for example, contribute to our essential services, fill our skill gaps and contribute taxes as well.

1491
01:45:25,271 --> 01:45:35,061
[SPEAKER_43]: Can you tell me how is setting strict migration limits for themselves or their close relatives beneficial when we still have these skill shortages, particularly in the NHS?

1492
01:45:36,222 --> 01:45:36,883
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, ma'am...

1493
01:45:41,318 --> 01:45:41,939
[SPEAKER_20]: You're absolutely right.

1494
01:45:42,640 --> 01:45:48,308
[SPEAKER_20]: Of course migrants can make a contribution to our country and do, like my parents, as you said, like my grandparents.

1495
01:45:48,849 --> 01:45:53,616
[SPEAKER_20]: My point is, though, that the levels of migration that we have seen are too high and they need to come down.

1496
01:45:54,076 --> 01:45:55,538
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's what we are now doing.

1497
01:45:55,759 --> 01:46:00,846
[SPEAKER_20]: If you look at the number of visas that we've issued at the start of this year, it's down by about 30%.

1498
01:46:00,826 --> 01:46:04,172
[SPEAKER_20]: The level of net migration is forecast to halve over the next 12 months.

1499
01:46:04,192 --> 01:46:11,203
[SPEAKER_20]: And if I'm elected, there will be a legal migration cap that we vote on in Parliament to guarantee that the numbers come down every year.

1500
01:46:11,343 --> 01:46:15,771
[SPEAKER_33]: But Prime Minister, I think the question here is about how... Tell me if I'm paraphrasing this wrong.

1501
01:46:15,931 --> 01:46:18,014
[SPEAKER_33]: It's about how to encourage the right kinds of workers here.

1502
01:46:18,054 --> 01:46:20,218
[SPEAKER_33]: And if you are not allowing them to bring their families...

1503
01:46:20,705 --> 01:46:22,006
[SPEAKER_33]: That is a serious disincentive.

1504
01:46:22,026 --> 01:46:23,107
[SPEAKER_33]: I think that's what you're saying, yes?

1505
01:46:24,348 --> 01:46:25,469
[SPEAKER_20]: No, but what we've done... Do you accept that?

1506
01:46:25,610 --> 01:46:27,091
[SPEAKER_20]: No, but that's not what we've done.

1507
01:46:27,131 --> 01:46:32,116
[SPEAKER_20]: What we have done is say that if people are going to bring family members here, they just need to be able to support them.

1508
01:46:32,876 --> 01:46:46,189
[SPEAKER_20]: I think that's reasonable, because any person that comes to our country obviously adds to the pressure on public services, and it's a very reasonable proposition to say, if people are bringing their dependents, family dependents, then they need to be able to demonstrate that they're going to be able to support them.

1509
01:46:46,209 --> 01:46:49,412
[SPEAKER_20]: That is, I think, a very common-sense measure, and that's what we are doing.

1510
01:46:49,392 --> 01:46:58,826
[SPEAKER_43]: That's OK, I understand that, and I agree with that, but then do you think that social workers, for example, coming from abroad should be paid more in order to be able to support their families?

1511
01:46:58,866 --> 01:47:07,158
[SPEAKER_43]: Because they won't be able to, on the kind of limits that you've put in place, given their salaries, they won't be able to support their families.

1512
01:47:07,178 --> 01:47:13,207
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, we have a dedicated visa for social care because we know how important it is, and we need to make sure that we do get the right workers here.

1513
01:47:13,427 --> 01:47:18,555
[SPEAKER_20]: That's why, unlike almost every other profession that you can think of, there's a dedicated visa for social care workers.

1514
01:47:18,535 --> 01:47:22,462
[SPEAKER_33]: Will they have to abide by this rule about supporting their families as well?

1515
01:47:22,623 --> 01:47:26,189
[SPEAKER_33]: Because the point you're making is they won't necessarily be able to afford to do that on their salary.

1516
01:47:26,249 --> 01:47:36,809
[SPEAKER_20]: And what we've seen is there are lots of people who are prepared to come to our country because it's a fantastic country to fill those vacancies and don't need to bring their family members and those are the people that we will welcome here.

1517
01:47:37,049 --> 01:47:41,978
[SPEAKER_20]: But what we can't do is support an unlimited number of people coming here who are not working.

1518
01:47:41,958 --> 01:47:43,960
[SPEAKER_20]: That's just simply not right, and it's not fair.

1519
01:47:44,241 --> 01:47:48,826
[SPEAKER_20]: So we may disagree on this, but I do think migration has to come down from the levels we've seen.

1520
01:47:49,166 --> 01:47:51,289
[SPEAKER_20]: That's what our migration cap will deliver.

1521
01:47:51,489 --> 01:47:52,770
[SPEAKER_20]: That's what we're already doing.

1522
01:47:52,790 --> 01:47:59,918
[SPEAKER_20]: And I think basic things like expecting people to support their family if they're bringing them here is actually just fair to everybody, and that's why I believe it's the right thing to do.

1523
01:48:00,279 --> 01:48:02,101
[SPEAKER_33]: Woman here.

1524
01:48:02,121 --> 01:48:02,181
[SPEAKER_38]: Hi.

1525
01:48:02,201 --> 01:48:05,825
[SPEAKER_38]: My daughter has lived in Australia, now working in Singapore.

1526
01:48:06,826 --> 01:48:08,488
[SPEAKER_38]: In both of those countries,

1527
01:48:09,127 --> 01:48:23,166
[SPEAKER_38]: Without sponsors or a job, there are no benefits, there's no health care as such, and therefore it attracts people that want to go to work hard to live there.

1528
01:48:24,148 --> 01:48:33,160
[SPEAKER_38]: In terms of the UK, we do need migration, especially for the lower paid jobs, because our lazy lot won't do it.

1529
01:48:33,410 --> 01:48:35,774
[SPEAKER_33]: Are you talking about our audience here?

1530
01:48:35,794 --> 01:48:36,174
[SPEAKER_38]: I do hope not.

1531
01:48:36,194 --> 01:48:36,915
[SPEAKER_38]: Maybe some of them.

1532
01:48:39,259 --> 01:48:41,763
[SPEAKER_38]: Oh, a fighting talker, OK. Who knows?

1533
01:48:41,783 --> 01:49:01,392
[SPEAKER_38]: What I can't grasp is, regarding the illegal immigration, if we didn't have similar policies introduced, perhaps the attraction for the illegal immigrants, it wouldn't go through the torturous journeys that they do, and we'd be in the situation now.

1534
01:49:01,675 --> 01:49:05,039
[SPEAKER_38]: where most of this election, I feel, is about immigration.

1535
01:49:06,381 --> 01:49:11,026
[SPEAKER_38]: Why can we not be stricter as other countries are?

1536
01:49:11,046 --> 01:49:12,308
[SPEAKER_38]: And it works.

1537
01:49:12,328 --> 01:49:15,512
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes, well, ma'am, that's exactly what I want to deliver, because you're right.

1538
01:49:16,192 --> 01:49:17,294
[SPEAKER_20]: Illegal immigration is wrong.

1539
01:49:17,794 --> 01:49:24,983
[SPEAKER_20]: When people jump the queue and come to our country illegally, it undermines the notion, the sense of fairness that our entire country is built on.

1540
01:49:24,963 --> 01:49:29,249
[SPEAKER_20]: And of course, it puts pressure on public services and it causes security issues.

1541
01:49:29,269 --> 01:49:30,892
[SPEAKER_20]: But fundamentally, it's wrong and it's unfair.

1542
01:49:31,012 --> 01:49:32,114
[SPEAKER_20]: That's why I want to stop it.

1543
01:49:32,134 --> 01:49:48,338
[SPEAKER_20]: Now, we've made progress, but in order to fix the problem that you've identified, actually mimicking something that Australia did for a while as well, we need to be able to remove people who come here illegally, send them somewhere else that's safe, because that removes the incentive.

1544
01:49:48,318 --> 01:49:49,479
[SPEAKER_20]: You're talking about Rwanda, Prime Minister, yes.

1545
01:49:49,499 --> 01:49:51,241
[SPEAKER_20]: That removes the incentive for them to come in the first place.

1546
01:49:51,461 --> 01:49:56,465
[SPEAKER_20]: Now, if I'm your Prime Minister, we have flights ready to go that will take illegal migrants to Rwanda.

1547
01:49:56,906 --> 01:50:02,010
[SPEAKER_20]: If Keir Starmer is your Prime Minister, the illegal migrants that we've been detained will be out on the streets.

1548
01:50:02,050 --> 01:50:03,151
[SPEAKER_20]: They won't be on those planes.

1549
01:50:03,271 --> 01:50:11,078
[SPEAKER_20]: We will become the soft touch of Europe just at a time when multiple other European countries are agreeing that our approach is the right approach.

1550
01:50:11,099 --> 01:50:14,462
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's what I want to deliver for you as your Prime Minister, if you give me the chance.

1551
01:50:14,482 --> 01:50:18,325
[SPEAKER_38]: And I do believe that you would be able to deliver

1552
01:50:18,305 --> 01:50:23,272
[SPEAKER_38]: Which brings me to my next question.

1553
01:50:23,593 --> 01:50:24,694
[SPEAKER_20]: Why did you call the election early?

1554
01:50:25,115 --> 01:50:34,708
[SPEAKER_20]: I called the election because, going back to the second question, my number one job when I became your Prime Minister was make sure we had economic stability.

1555
01:50:35,770 --> 01:50:44,262
[SPEAKER_20]: When we had that, when inflation was effectively back to normal as it was, the economy was growing healthily, wages were rising, I thought that was the right moment for us to consider our future.

1556
01:50:44,242 --> 01:50:44,803
[SPEAKER_20]: You have a choice.

1557
01:50:44,863 --> 01:50:46,185
[SPEAKER_20]: You and everyone else has a choice.

1558
01:50:46,405 --> 01:50:47,907
[SPEAKER_20]: Do we build on the progress we've made?

1559
01:50:47,927 --> 01:50:49,509
[SPEAKER_20]: I want to keep cutting your taxes.

1560
01:50:49,810 --> 01:50:54,797
[SPEAKER_20]: The alternative, if Keir Starmer is your Prime Minister, is that your taxes are going to go up.

1561
01:50:54,817 --> 01:51:04,410
[SPEAKER_20]: That is the choice for everyone at this election and I'm going to fight very hard to make sure that I can continue the work that we've started, continue delivering financial security, continue cutting your taxes.

1562
01:51:04,762 --> 01:51:07,264
[SPEAKER_20]: Are you glad you called the election when you did?

1563
01:51:07,344 --> 01:51:08,225
[SPEAKER_20]: How do you think it's going?

1564
01:51:08,766 --> 01:51:12,209
[SPEAKER_20]: It was the right moment to call the election, for the reasons that I outlined.

1565
01:51:12,309 --> 01:51:13,750
[SPEAKER_20]: And Fiona, I am.

1566
01:51:13,951 --> 01:51:15,532
[SPEAKER_20]: Look, of course these things are difficult.

1567
01:51:15,552 --> 01:51:23,760
[SPEAKER_20]: But to actually answer the first question over there, when I was standing against Liz Truss in that leadership election, I had the same questions from everybody.

1568
01:51:24,240 --> 01:51:24,901
[SPEAKER_20]: You're behind.

1569
01:51:25,421 --> 01:51:26,142
[SPEAKER_20]: Why are you bothering?

1570
01:51:26,562 --> 01:51:28,884
[SPEAKER_20]: Isn't this all... You know, this is all very difficult.

1571
01:51:29,125 --> 01:51:31,647
[SPEAKER_20]: I said, no, well, I'm fighting for what I believe is right.

1572
01:51:31,627 --> 01:51:38,815
[SPEAKER_20]: Even though people didn't want to hear it at the time, I kept going, I kept saying what I thought was right for this country, I kept going to the end, and you know what?

1573
01:51:38,855 --> 01:51:39,856
[SPEAKER_20]: I was proved right then.

1574
01:51:40,597 --> 01:51:56,574
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's why you can trust me now when I say that what Keir Starmer is promising you is the same fantasy that Liz trusted, and it's just going to mean your taxes are going to go up, and that matters to me because I don't want that to happen, and that's why we're having this election, and that's what I'm going to keep fighting for.

1575
01:51:56,594 --> 01:51:58,196
[SPEAKER_33]: He obviously disputes that, but let's take a question from Edie Lewis.

1576
01:51:58,216 --> 01:51:59,237
[SPEAKER_33]: Edie Lewis.

1577
01:52:02,356 --> 01:52:04,302
[SPEAKER_33]: Oh, there you are, just a little bit further back, look.

1578
01:52:04,322 --> 01:52:05,506
[SPEAKER_33]: With the glasses, yeah.

1579
01:52:05,707 --> 01:52:11,826
[SPEAKER_39]: As Labour are predicted to win a landslide victory, do you have any regrets about any actions you've taken during your premiership?

1580
01:52:12,346 --> 01:52:13,267
[SPEAKER_20]: Sorry, what was your name?

1581
01:52:13,947 --> 01:52:14,528
[SPEAKER_20]: Edie.

1582
01:52:14,548 --> 01:52:14,708
[SPEAKER_20]: Edie.

1583
01:52:15,529 --> 01:52:16,610
[SPEAKER_20]: Any regrets, Prime Minister?

1584
01:52:16,630 --> 01:52:16,970
[SPEAKER_20]: Slightly.

1585
01:52:17,050 --> 01:52:17,431
[SPEAKER_20]: Of course.

1586
01:52:17,951 --> 01:52:21,354
[SPEAKER_20]: No one gets everything right, and I've been very open about that.

1587
01:52:21,374 --> 01:52:26,038
[SPEAKER_20]: And I completely understand people's frustrations with me, with the Conservative Party, with the last few years.

1588
01:52:26,058 --> 01:52:28,180
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, do you want to be open about what regrets you might have?

1589
01:52:28,200 --> 01:52:30,843
[SPEAKER_20]: But what this election is about is about the future.

1590
01:52:31,003 --> 01:52:35,687
[SPEAKER_33]: Now, we've been talking about various things, but fundamentally... Prime Minister, I'm sorry, because that's actually not the question.

1591
01:52:35,747 --> 01:52:39,611
[SPEAKER_33]: The question is, do you have any regrets about any decisions taken during your premiership?

1592
01:52:39,951 --> 01:52:42,353
[SPEAKER_33]: And you say you've been quite open, so perhaps you could be open with us

1593
01:52:42,333 --> 01:52:45,206
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, but look, everyone have their own views on it and this is not about that.

1594
01:52:45,226 --> 01:52:47,395
[SPEAKER_20]: What are your views?

1595
01:52:47,415 --> 01:52:49,625
[SPEAKER_20]: As I said, I wish we'd made more progress on the waiting list.

1596
01:52:50,770 --> 01:52:52,377
[SPEAKER_20]: I've been very open about that.

1597
01:52:52,643 --> 01:52:54,585
[SPEAKER_20]: I wish we had made more progress on the waiting list.

1598
01:52:54,625 --> 01:52:55,647
[SPEAKER_20]: It's something that was important to me.

1599
01:52:55,667 --> 01:52:57,489
[SPEAKER_20]: We haven't made as much progress as I would have liked.

1600
01:52:57,769 --> 01:53:00,052
[SPEAKER_20]: I've explained the reasons, and we're making progress now.

1601
01:53:00,332 --> 01:53:02,415
[SPEAKER_20]: But fundamentally, this election is about the future.

1602
01:53:03,135 --> 01:53:04,377
[SPEAKER_20]: I've had this job for 18 months.

1603
01:53:04,397 --> 01:53:05,178
[SPEAKER_20]: You've seen what I've done.

1604
01:53:05,218 --> 01:53:11,485
[SPEAKER_20]: My primary job, the most important task I had was to make sure our economy was back in good health, and it now is.

1605
01:53:11,866 --> 01:53:14,349
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's the thing that you have to think about going forward.

1606
01:53:14,589 --> 01:53:20,676
[SPEAKER_20]: We're in a position now, as I said I would, I said once we got things back to where they were, we could start cutting your taxes.

1607
01:53:20,656 --> 01:53:23,180
[SPEAKER_20]: And we've put out a proposal, and Fiona, this is really important.

1608
01:53:23,200 --> 01:53:25,443
[SPEAKER_33]: I think you've made that point already, that's the only thing I was going to say.

1609
01:53:25,463 --> 01:53:29,329
[SPEAKER_20]: But it's important to me, because people are asking about the election, right?

1610
01:53:29,529 --> 01:53:31,692
[SPEAKER_20]: That is the important issue at stake in this election.

1611
01:53:32,073 --> 01:53:42,167
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm going to continue cutting taxes for people at every stage of their lives, whether you're a pensioner, whether you're in work, whether you're setting up a small business if you're self-employed, whether you're a young couple trying to buy your first home.

1612
01:53:42,388 --> 01:53:44,731
[SPEAKER_20]: I want to cut your taxes and deliver financial security.

1613
01:53:45,052 --> 01:53:49,498
[SPEAKER_20]: The alternative is Keir Starmer, who is going to put your taxes up, as we've seen over the years,

1614
01:53:49,478 --> 01:53:51,140
[SPEAKER_20]: which he disputes, I have to say.

1615
01:53:51,200 --> 01:53:51,841
[SPEAKER_20]: He's also just been here.

1616
01:53:51,861 --> 01:53:55,727
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, he's spent the last three days avoiding telling anyone about putting up council tax.

1617
01:53:55,807 --> 01:53:56,067
[SPEAKER_20]: All right.

1618
01:53:56,147 --> 01:54:00,213
[SPEAKER_33]: And that is what's coming, and I'm going to fight very hard to make sure that doesn't happen.

1619
01:54:00,233 --> 01:54:03,077
[SPEAKER_33]: With the biggest tax take on the Conservative government, as you know, for many years.

1620
01:54:03,397 --> 01:54:04,378
[SPEAKER_33]: Yes, woman here.

1621
01:54:04,398 --> 01:54:06,441
[SPEAKER_40]: So, I'm just going back a step.

1622
01:54:06,922 --> 01:54:18,017
[SPEAKER_40]: Are you really considering leaving the ECHR to push forward your Rwanda policy, which, let's be honest, is devoid of strategic thinking and just is inhumane?

1623
01:54:17,997 --> 01:54:26,431
[SPEAKER_20]: You are talking about the European Court of Human Rights.

1624
01:54:26,771 --> 01:54:28,995
[SPEAKER_20]: Do you know what happened last month?

1625
01:54:29,736 --> 01:54:34,183
[SPEAKER_20]: 15 other European countries all signed a statement about illegal migration.

1626
01:54:34,865 --> 01:54:35,506
[SPEAKER_20]: Do you know what they said?

1627
01:54:36,307 --> 01:54:38,250
[SPEAKER_20]: All of them agreed

1628
01:54:38,737 --> 01:54:54,060
[SPEAKER_20]: Italy, Netherlands, lots of other countries, all of them agreed that having the ability to remove illegal migrants to a safe third country was an important part of the solution to this problem, because it removes the incentive for them to come in the first place.

1629
01:54:54,641 --> 01:54:55,743
[SPEAKER_20]: So you have your view.

1630
01:54:55,763 --> 01:54:56,364
[SPEAKER_20]: I disagree.

1631
01:54:56,384 --> 01:54:58,307
[SPEAKER_33]: You're being asked, would you leave the European Court of Human Rights?

1632
01:54:58,327 --> 01:54:59,148
[SPEAKER_33]: I'm going to get on to that.

1633
01:54:59,168 --> 01:55:01,091
[SPEAKER_20]: But you said that you had a point about the policy.

1634
01:55:01,111 --> 01:55:02,573
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm just telling you, I disagree with you.

1635
01:55:02,593 --> 01:55:07,140
[SPEAKER_20]: 15 other European countries just a few weeks ago decided that they agree with me.

1636
01:55:07,120 --> 01:55:09,644
[SPEAKER_20]: Did the Supreme Court call it unlawful?

1637
01:55:09,664 --> 01:55:16,074
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, I've been crystal clear, and that's why we've passed a new piece of legislation to address the concerns of our court, because I respect our court.

1638
01:55:16,375 --> 01:55:22,385
[SPEAKER_20]: They raised concerns, that's why we passed a new piece of legislation, and that's why their flights will now go if I'm Prime Minister.

1639
01:55:22,625 --> 01:55:25,129
[SPEAKER_20]: And when it comes to the ECHR, I am crystal clear.

1640
01:55:25,109 --> 01:55:42,028
[SPEAKER_20]: I believe everything that we are doing is in compliance with our international obligations, but if a foreign court, including the European Court, forces me to choose between our country's national security and membership of that court, I'm going to choose this country's national security every single time.

1641
01:55:42,228 --> 01:55:44,012
[SPEAKER_33]: So when you say it's a foreign court...

1642
01:55:45,916 --> 01:55:53,247
[SPEAKER_33]: Just to be clear, when you say it's a foreign court, it's a court that we were part of setting up as Great Britain, as the United Kingdom.

1643
01:55:53,428 --> 01:55:55,331
[SPEAKER_33]: It also has a British judge sitting on it.

1644
01:55:55,671 --> 01:55:57,674
[SPEAKER_33]: So I'm just wondering why you call it a foreign court.

1645
01:55:57,995 --> 01:55:59,717
[SPEAKER_33]: It's a court that we were part of establishing.

1646
01:55:59,858 --> 01:56:01,400
[SPEAKER_20]: But it is in Strasbourg, Fiona.

1647
01:56:01,440 --> 01:56:02,802
[SPEAKER_20]: That means it's not a British court.

1648
01:56:02,822 --> 01:56:04,665
[SPEAKER_33]: It's not a court that has nothing to do with us.

1649
01:56:04,685 --> 01:56:06,187
[SPEAKER_33]: We were absolutely instrumental in setting it up.

1650
01:56:06,528 --> 01:56:07,890
[SPEAKER_20]: My point is very clear.

1651
01:56:07,870 --> 01:56:15,878
[SPEAKER_20]: I believe everything we're doing is in compliance with our rules and regulations, but this issue is too important to not to be able to grip.

1652
01:56:15,898 --> 01:56:18,301
[SPEAKER_20]: I want to deliver on the thing that I promised you I would deliver on.

1653
01:56:18,321 --> 01:56:22,645
[SPEAKER_20]: I want to get these flights off, build this incentive, or remove the incentive, build the deterrent.

1654
01:56:22,825 --> 01:56:24,367
[SPEAKER_20]: It's the only way to solve this problem.

1655
01:56:24,387 --> 01:56:26,389
[SPEAKER_20]: Now, you and I disagree on that, right?

1656
01:56:26,509 --> 01:56:28,591
[SPEAKER_20]: You think it's fine for people to come and they shouldn't be removed.

1657
01:56:28,851 --> 01:56:29,612
[SPEAKER_20]: That's your decision.

1658
01:56:29,912 --> 01:56:35,498
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't think that's right for our country, and that's why I'm prepared to do what it takes to get this problem resolved.

1659
01:56:36,372 --> 01:56:36,853
[SPEAKER_33]: Sorry, let's go.

1660
01:56:36,913 --> 01:56:37,754
[SPEAKER_33]: You're saying you didn't say that.

1661
01:56:38,134 --> 01:56:40,457
[SPEAKER_40]: No, I said, are you considering leaving the ECHR?

1662
01:56:40,717 --> 01:56:41,618
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, I think we've had...

1663
01:56:41,638 --> 01:56:42,319
[SPEAKER_33]: I did say, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

1664
01:56:42,339 --> 01:56:42,919
[SPEAKER_33]: I've heard that very clearly.

1665
01:56:42,939 --> 01:56:44,121
[SPEAKER_40]: But you just put words in my mouth then.

1666
01:56:44,401 --> 01:56:44,962
[SPEAKER_33]: OK. All right.

1667
01:56:44,982 --> 01:56:45,763
[SPEAKER_33]: But we...

1668
01:56:45,783 --> 01:56:46,604
[SPEAKER_33]: I appreciate what you're saying.

1669
01:56:46,684 --> 01:56:46,904
[SPEAKER_40]: Yeah.

1670
01:56:47,525 --> 01:56:50,608
[SPEAKER_33]: And there's a man over there looking very keen to say something with a black T-shirt.

1671
01:56:50,688 --> 01:56:50,888
[SPEAKER_33]: Yeah.

1672
01:56:52,891 --> 01:56:53,632
[SPEAKER_33]: Off you go.

1673
01:56:53,652 --> 01:56:55,033
[SPEAKER_14]: It's just a point I'd like to make.

1674
01:56:55,694 --> 01:57:00,479
[SPEAKER_14]: There's only two other countries in the world that don't subscribe to the ECHR.

1675
01:57:00,499 --> 01:57:01,941
[SPEAKER_14]: Russia and Belarus.

1676
01:57:11,776 --> 01:57:19,886
[SPEAKER_20]: Sir, with the greatest respect, we do not need a foreign court to tell us how to police our borders and our security.

1677
01:57:20,547 --> 01:57:24,371
[SPEAKER_20]: And I believe that everything we're doing is in compliance with our international obligations.

1678
01:57:24,672 --> 01:57:31,740
[SPEAKER_20]: But if I'm put in a position where I'm forced to choose between those things, I'm going to put our country's national security first every single time.

1679
01:57:31,820 --> 01:57:34,223
[SPEAKER_20]: And I make absolutely no apology about that.

1680
01:57:37,358 --> 01:57:38,419
[SPEAKER_33]: I've got about 30 seconds left.

1681
01:57:38,660 --> 01:57:39,421
[SPEAKER_33]: Very quick question.

1682
01:57:40,402 --> 01:57:49,974
[SPEAKER_24]: I'm 19, so I'm too old to do National Service, if you did bring that in, and I'm not looking to get a mortgage in the next Parliament, so anything to do with that wouldn't impact me.

1683
01:57:49,994 --> 01:57:56,883
[SPEAKER_24]: Is there any policy you can offer me that would positively impact my life and the life of people who are my age?

1684
01:57:57,403 --> 01:57:58,885
[SPEAKER_33]: OK. Forgive me, because we're pretty much out of time.

1685
01:57:58,965 --> 01:57:59,586
[SPEAKER_33]: Could you name one?

1686
01:58:00,608 --> 01:58:02,590
[SPEAKER_20]: Are you studying at the moment?

1687
01:58:03,177 --> 01:58:03,738
[SPEAKER_20]: Where are you studying?

1688
01:58:04,499 --> 01:58:04,659
[SPEAKER_20]: Here.

1689
01:58:04,679 --> 01:58:05,319
[SPEAKER_20]: Oh, you're at your uni.

1690
01:58:05,580 --> 01:58:06,581
[SPEAKER_20]: OK. And what work do you want to do?

1691
01:58:06,601 --> 01:58:08,143
[SPEAKER_33]: Sadly, we don't have time for these niceties.

1692
01:58:08,503 --> 01:58:09,084
[SPEAKER_33]: One policy.

1693
01:58:09,464 --> 01:58:10,846
[SPEAKER_20]: You know what?

1694
01:58:11,026 --> 01:58:13,249
[SPEAKER_20]: Very simply, when you get your job, I'm going to cut your taxes.

1695
01:58:13,269 --> 01:58:15,371
[SPEAKER_20]: You're going to keep more of your money and spend it on whatever you want.

1696
01:58:15,571 --> 01:58:16,072
[SPEAKER_20]: There you go.

1697
01:58:16,572 --> 01:58:17,073
[SPEAKER_33]: All right.

1698
01:58:17,533 --> 01:58:20,617
[SPEAKER_33]: So you've got something to answer, so I had to cut it short.

1699
01:58:21,098 --> 01:58:22,559
[SPEAKER_33]: That is it for now.

1700
01:58:22,639 --> 01:58:25,422
[SPEAKER_33]: Well done for all your stamina, folks, for sticking with the two hours.

1701
01:58:25,443 --> 01:58:26,083
[SPEAKER_33]: Thank you for your questions.

1702
01:58:26,344 --> 01:58:29,387
[SPEAKER_33]: Prime Minister, thank you very much for taking part in this.

1703
01:58:29,468 --> 01:58:41,388
[SPEAKER_33]: That is our Leaders special over for now, but don't forget, we have got the Plaid Cymru special on BBC World on Monday, we're back on Thursday for the usual routine, and then Friday with Question Time, and they're both from Birmingham.

1704
01:58:41,408 --> 01:58:46,817
[SPEAKER_33]: The first, our usual programme, and then the second, remember, with Nigel Farage of Reform UK and Aidan Ramsey of The Greens.

1705
01:58:46,917 --> 01:58:51,725
[SPEAKER_33]: But for now, from all of us here, and Prime Minister, thank you very much.

1706
01:58:52,165 --> 01:58:52,506
[SPEAKER_33]: Bye-bye.

